You don't know how you know.
but you know 'you' are dead, that these are all of your past lives, and for some reason you are watching you next life.
The 'you' after you.
You observe the development of this fresh new existence.
It's surreal.
Well, even more surreal than being dead and being in a room with all of your past selves.
Why are you here?
Why are you observing this fresh existence?
You can't change it, can't help them.
You are only able to observe.
You look around.
You observe your previous versions, all of them witnessing the beginning of a fresh existence.
Some seem more focused than others.
You are curious about whether or not they will be reincarnated once more.
Wait, where did that though come from.
If they were all you, then how could they be someone else too?
You glance back at the monitor.
The person is grown now in living in a large city; much larger than any you ever lived in.
That got you thinking, about the number of people in the world, and how they all must have souls.
You are curious if you are the sole person present in this space.
The only soul that is; are you all just one soul with multiple bodies?
That didn't feel like the right answer.
You glance around the room once more.
You felt you were definitely connected to them all, but also very different.

And you thought about all the past yous, and all the past lives of everyone you ever met, and why you would be here watching another life, getting the chance to learn from their mistakes as well as your own.
And that's when it came to you.
You watched one of your former selves suddenly smile, and walk through the exit door fading out.
And you noticed a new movie screen appear in the room, next to the first and another new life started playing out.
Everyone was connected.
Connected to each other, the past, and the future.
A soul gives birth to another, its twin at first, but then growing and changing as all twins do.
It was a web of life, and you helped to shape it as well as be shaped by it.
With that understanding you looked back at the movies and learned.
Soon, you too walked through the exit, and though the revelation about souls faded from your mind the feeling of connection, and caring for others as yourself remained.
A new life began.
The alien's name is Rayne.
She works as a bounty hunter.
She's a little bit wacky too.
She has it in her head that Matt Damon is the greatest bounty of the human race given his amazing comedic skill and acting talent.
So she believes that kidnapping Matt Damon and bringing him back to her home planet, Cyborg, is the best way for her to make it rain and for her to get a payday.
She is unaware that people will do anything to bring Matt Damon back.

The human race is going to make it extremely difficult for Rayne to actually cash out on her payday since they are going to make it near impossible to actually get the bounty owed to her for kidnapping him.
In fact, the human race, upon discovering the Matt Damon is not home, immediately assembled task forces around the world to try to locate Matt Damon's exact location.
It takes the human race forever to find out where Matt Damon is, but once they do, they will send one of their best agents to retrieve him.
The human race pinpoints Matt Damon's exact location on the spacecraft that the alien has taken off with him in.
They later realize that the spaceship is on course for Cyborg, a destination in the Andromeda Galaxy.
Due to the distance it takes so long for them to figure out where Matt Damon is, they send an elite human agent after him, who eventually catches up.
This elite agent's name is Barth.
Barth has a storied pedigree and is an incredibly talented agent.
He has never lost a case before and he is not about to let Matt Damon be the first.
So Barth heads off to catch up with the alien on his own personal spacecraft.
Barth successfully locates and catches up with the alien.
Rayne is totally shocked to see Barth standing in her way of cashing out on the kidnapping.
How dare this mere mortal human try to thwart her plans for cash?
Barth tells the alien to let go of Matt Damon, or things could get really ugly.
Barth believes he's the one calling the shots, despite the alien believing she's the one in control.
The two bicker for a bit and then the alien realizes that this whole situation is just fruitless.
Therefore, she consents to letting Matt Damon go.
After being freed, Matt Damon informs the alien and Barth that he intends to return to his home.
He is fed up with this situation of being taken against his will.
He plans to return home and possibly begin building a family.
Perhaps he will meet a kind female companion and decide to start a family.
The alien feels great sadness as Matt Damon leaves.
But Barth totally understands Matt Damon's desire to settle down with some semblance of normalcy after the bizarre kidnapping experience that he's just gone through.
Barth promises to take Matt Damon back to his hometown on planet Earth so that Matt Damon can recuperate and regain his mental health after such a harrowing experience.
Before departing for Earth, Matt Damon inquires with the alien about her well-being.
The alien, sad as she is about Matt Damon's departure, smiles at Matt Damon and nods.
The alien knows that Matt Damon is actually quite the gentleman.
If anyone had to escape her capture, it was a good thing it was Matt Damon, since the alien had actually grown somewhat of a soft spot for the man.
The extraterrestrial observes the departure of Matt Damon, Barth, and the spaceship.
Barth takes Matt Damon home, and Matt Damon rests, relaxes and tries to forget the whole experience of ever having been kidnapped.
When Barth checks in on Matt Damon a few months later, Matt Damon seems to be in very good spirits and is as good as new.
It's almost as though he was never kidnapped.
Everyone has their own preference, however i like being able to listen to a book because it allows me to do other things while i listen.
When you are physically reading a book, you cannot really multitask.
When you have four kids, two dogs, and a wife you are really just trying to be as efficient as you can throughout the day.
Being able to plug in and hear a nice book while doing house work or walking the dogs is great!
I feel i am able to improve myself as a person without stressing myself out over loosing time for tasks.
Not only this, but it has given me a full library of books to choose from that i would need to physically go to the library to have access to.
Another reason i personally prefer audiobooks is the fact that the titles are cheaper to buy on the audiobook platform than they are to buy physical copies for.
This is a no brainer since it costs to print the actual book.
So to me, it is really all pros when it comes to audiobooks, and they fit into my life like a puzzle piece.
If you have a hectic schedule but still desire to expand your knowledge, audiobooks are a great option.
There are no real disadvantages for me personally.
This being said i understand the perspective of someone who would prefer physically reading a book.
Being able to immerse yourself in the book in complete silence is a very therapeutic experience.
This alone by itself may be something that helps enhances someone's calm and i understand that.
Not everyone likes to multi task all the time, and for some people reading is just something that allows them to get their minds off of things and focus on one thing.
I have had my moments like this, and for this situation maybe reading is the way to go, or even using an audiobook and just closing your eyes.
I am a very overactive person, so the thought of not being productive can stress me out.
This is why i like using the audiobooks when i am doing other things.
I feel i get more of the book when i listen when going for a drive or for a run.
If you are pushing yourself during a run sometimes all you want to think about is the book to not think about how you are running up this gigantic hill and you have more hills to go.
Sure you can listen to any music, but there is something about listening to a book that all ties into one intricate picture in my head when i run.
Its like the feeling of being completely immersed in a movie.
Add the runners high to this and you feel like a million bucks.
There are a number of reasons why I think this way.
The first reason is simply convenience.
You can store thousands of books right onto your phone without taking up much space and they are available anytime in a very organized easy to find way.
Other reasons would be because I can listen to them while commuting, working out, walking on the beach, and doing pretty much anything else.

I am sure reading has its benefits as well and I still do plenty of that in the forms of email, reports, news and other vital/interesting information but after doing that all day I do not want to go home and cozy up with a nice book and read some more.
No, I want to cook dinner and listen to how the universe came into existence or listen to a short sci fi novella from the 1980's.
I can do all this while taking care of my most basic needs and learning new and exciting things on a daily basis.
That's why I prefer audio books.
This was very exciting for me.
I couldn't wait to see who I would become next.
I was anticipating something exciting, such as a renowned soccer player or a celebrity musician.
But I wasn't famous at all.
I was a boy in a small village in the mountains of Nepal.
I lived a very simple life with my family in a house that my parents built from wood that we gathered.
I was truly upset to realize how financially deprived I was.
But the boy I would become was not sad at all.
He enjoyed his simple life.
He was happy with his family and friends in the village in the mountains.
And then I realized that this boy does in fact have a peaceful life.
He isn't sad about not being famous.
He cares more about the life he has.
I came to the realization that I should emulate his behavior.
But wait I was him.
Perhaps in this next life I learned how to be happy with what I have.
I, when playing the boy on the screen, learned that I should be grateful for what I have, instead of wanting more.
And the boy was happy.
He had no interest in attaining fame.
He wasn't concerned about being wealthy.
And I thought that this was great.
I looked around in the theater and saw that everyone else was happy too.
All of the previous versions of me were rejoicing in their seats as it seemed my soul had learned a valuable lesson.
I was pleased to gain a new perspective on my life.
I continued watching in the theater until the next life.
And I never had to relearn the lesson of gratitude again.
The ancient gods' mystical powers are making a comeback.
In order to use it, however, the humans must humble themselves.
Mana only flows through those who understand the nature of life: humans, animals, plants, and elements all must work together to take care of Earth.
The humans visit the old libraries in Greece in order to learn more about Mana.
Along the way, they irrigate and replenish food supplies for the animals.
They are doing what they can to ensure that the species who survived the alien attack can continue living.
Their journey to Greece takes several weeks since they have to cross the Atlantic Ocean by boat.
They are heartbroken when they realize what their consumer lifestyle has done to the oceans.
They gather all of the garbage that they can so that fish and water fowl have better living environments.
Upon reaching Greece, they make their way to the ancient library.
It's near some monuments to the Gods, so they decide to study there.
They hoped that the Gods who could teach them how to use Mana would take pity on them and recognize all of the work they had done for the planet and for their own self-improvement.
They are taken aback by the sudden appearance of the Gods.
They are shocked to learn that the Gods have no plans to teach them how to use Mana.
The humans must figure out how to operate it independently.
The Gods vanish, leaving humans to fend for themselves.
In despair, the humans look to each other for support.
They realize that the past few months of self-improvement have not been enough to erase the past damage they have done.
They need to put in more effort to deserve Mana.
The humans realize that they must adapt to coexist peacefully with the Earth.
They need to understand how to coexist peacefully with the animals, plants, and natural elements.
They need to figure out how to coexist peacefully with one another.
If they can do this, then maybe, just maybe, the Gods will give them one more chance.
We can focus on both at the same time.
We don't have to put all of our focus towards one topic.
Animal cruelty is horrible just like cruelty against humans is horrible.
No living thing should be harmed physically, mentally or spiritually by another living thing.
But again, I think we can help animals and humans at the same time.
We can rescue animals from shelters instead of buying them off breeders.
We can help get rid of the drug problem that causes so much crime.
I am not surprised to learn that humans are more empathetic towards animals compared to other humans.
I think that probably stems from humans having more positive experiences with animals and more negative experiences with humans.
There's news stories every single day that talk about all the horrible things that the human species does including murder, war, robbery, etc.
That sours humans for a lot of us.
While I personally believe that every human has some good in them, I know that many others don't feel that way at all.
I think that many humans also consider their pets as part of their family.
I know I do.
If I saw my dog getting beaten by a baseball bat I'd do everything in my power to save him.
If I saw another human getting beaten by a baseball bat, I'd also try to help.
If I was forced to choose, I'd have to help my dog simply because I consider my dog to be family.
I know many other people think that way too.
Dogs are the best.
They aren't known as mans best friend for no reason.
Most dogs are more loyal than most humans.
That's a sad fact.
As humans we should be doing everything we can do help end animal cruelty.
An animal can't defend itself against a human in most cases and anyone that would harm an animal is a despicable person.
Lets focus on animal welfare and lets focus on lowering human suffering.
Lets make the world a better place.
Animals have different defenses than humans, and they are not as capable of defending themselves.
The chances that the animal brought the abuse on themselves are impossible.
Humans have the ability to protect themselves and can make decisions about whether or not to take a certain action.
And in the case of humans, they have the ability to speak up for themselves.
I think any empathetic person would defend any living being that is suffering abuse, whether human or animal.
In some cases, it could be assumed that the human did something to bring the injury on themselves in cases such as revenge.
However, many times humans are attacked by other people, they are defenseless and helpless.
I think the focus should be on the assailant.
Anyone that harms an animal needs help , and I think that they should be punished.
There could be some debate about sentences for animal crimes versus human crimes.
However, I think that the focus should be on the person that committed the crime and their motivations for their actions.
I think that it is important to focus on both human and animal welfare equally.

Throughout the entire duration, Matt Damon is compelled to reside in an unfamiliar environment alongside a peculiar extraterrestrial being.
He is angry about all the deliberation going on in the world, and no action to save him.
When the humans capture the alien's wife and a bold rescue is planned, Matt Damon finds himself transformed from a reluctant captive.
He suddenly becomes a prisoner of war.
The aliens torture him relentlessly.
Not being aware of time, he is unable to keep track of how much time has passed since arriving on the unfamiliar planet belonging to the alien.
He begins to look back over his life and realizes that he has played so many different characters, he never thought that he would live a real life scenario like this, in front of the whole world.
He gathers his composure and decides that he will act, and give his best performance, as a hero.
He will rescue the world from the extraterrestrial that has abducted him.
He requests an audience with the head alien and promises to divulge everything he knows about Earth's defenses at the meeting.
The aliens agree and take him to their leader.
Matt Damon is positioned on the ground facing the alien leader alongside a translator.
He begins by complimenting the alien leader on his command over his people.
He then launches into a scene he had prepared for the occasion.
He seizes the alien ruler's antenna, which is believed to represent his authority, and hurls it down to the ground.
He screams, 'Freedom!'
so loudly that he startles the guards.
Afterwards, he steps back and begins acting out a scene in which his character, the protagonist, is shouting at the leader of the aliens.
He tells the alien leader that the people of Earth will never surrender!
He declares that they will continue fighting until every last man, woman, and child is involved.
The alien leader picks up his torn antennae and grabs Matt in one hand and lifts him over his head.
He stares into Matt's eyes and tells him that the aliens had taken him because he is an advocate for environmentalism.
He claims that the inhabitants of Earth lacked an understanding of how to engage with their environment.
The purpose of taking Matt was to give him the knowledge to protect the natural environment of the planet.
The fight didn't start until Earthlings kidnapped his wife.
He informs Matt that unless Earthlings transition to a more eco-conscious society, their populations will need to be sacrificed in order to preserve the planet.
Matt listened carefully, feeling quite the fool.
He agreed to deliver the message and get the alien's wife back.
The aliens let him go and the leader's wife is returned.
Matt learns how to save the planet and delivers the message, but nobody listens.
The media ostracizes and mocks him for his perceived 'brainwashing.'
The Earth burns down 20 years later.

This little pig became depressed.
He lived alone in a house constructed of depleted uranium, so he didn't have any companions.
What a lonely existence he faced.
The 92nd little pig woke up every day to the same disappointing life.
He thought of ending it all, but he was passionate about the cause he had protested against so many times.
He would not do anything to support baconism.
The baconists would not have him for breakfast, not today and not ever.
Still, the 92nd little pig struggled to find the will to live.
His bacon lives matter work was meaningful, but did not fulfill his innermost needs.
He had never had a close friend, or even a visitor to his home.
He lived in shame, and had been unable to form strong relationships, with anyone.
He had never experienced romantic love before.
He had never experienced being in a romantic partnership before.
He had never been on a date before.
His world was built of isolated despair, with a foundation in depleted uranium.
The 92nd little pig wept at night, until he fell asleep.
He woke up to the horrible realization that he would have to live another day on this mound of cancerous toxicity.
He will need to confront the world once more.
He looked for reasons to leave the house each day.
He would go for a trough, at the local troughery, even when he wasn't hungry.
He would chat with the person serving his food, but he could never come to terms with his shoddy foundation and never allowed a true friendship to form.
He regularly visited the nearby pub, where he would drink excessively and then throw up on the street.
This led to both physical and emotional ruin.
After several years of crippling addiction, the 92nd little pig died alone, on a park bench which was later revealed to be mildly radioactive and had to be removed.
Nobody remembers the 92nd little pig.
I personally feel that it is less problematic to not pay college athletes and for this reason i would side with not paying them.
However, i think the root of the problem just comes with the large amount of money schools make off of these college athletes.
NCAA is one of the highest payed organizations in the world, and much of this is because they dont have to pay their athletes.
This makes people refer to the athletes almost like they are being taken advantage of.

I understand the perspective of the athlete being taken advantage of, however they are still given the platform to demonstrate their skills, and also given the opportunity to play in front of large crowds and meet tons of people, and build a following on social media.
Many perks come with being a college athlete aside from just possibly being paid.
The free tuition is nice for the athlete, however i dont know how much paying the athletes would be helpful.
Would they be paid based off of talent, or just a flat fee?
If it was a flat fee, the athletes would probably want more anyway if they were the star players.
I am personally a former college football player as well, and I just feel that it is not necessary to pay the players.
I think it would be nice to have more in place for the athletes, but not necessarily just a pay check.
I know there are some athletes who can barely afford college and food while being there.
This is unexceptable to me if they are part of a team making that much money for the university.
I would treat it like a job and simply provide the best working conditions for athletes that do a lot to help the school run.
No student athlete at all should have to worry about getting food to eat, or having a place to stay.
I believe that this is a satisfactory solution to the issue.
Using some of the money to give back to athletes instead of giving athletes the freedom to spend on whatever they wish.

I am for the side of not paying athletes because i think there are too many variables associated with the amount you would pay them, and it is also sort of starting a bidding process right out of high school.
College would almost be like the pros in a way if you could get paid like a professional athlete.
If anything i think a flat fee would be most fair for everyone who was a part of the actual team.
This way, nobody is glorified in the amount that they are paid.
This would literally create powerhouses and the same schools would win every year just because they have the most money.
I think it would be a good idea to have a stipend for the athletes as well, just to make sure that they are able to make ends meet.
Just more structured types of payment that is more equal to all of the players on the team.
There are simply too many downsides of paying each player based off of their value, and i dont think it would be something that would be easy to bounce back from for the NCAA.
All this being said, the NCAA has to stop being stingy with their money and simply treat the athletes better.
If this was the case, this would not even be a discussion.
In conclusion however, i feel that the NCAA should not pay college athletes, at least in the same way pro players are paid.
I would say that we are slightly irresponsible in a worldly, or even local way if we don't keep up with the news though.
That is because we are not being informed of what is going on in our community, and we are not able to make the best decisions for ourselves, our family, and our community.
If we do not keep up with the news, we could end up making bad choices without even being aware that we are making a bad choice.

For example, if we are not aware of the current events in our community, we could end up moving into a bad neighborhood, or buying a house that is in a very bad school district, or without knowing there is a high crime rate where we are moving.

Another example of not paying attention to the news is that we could end up buying a product that is not good for us, or even buying a product that is made in a way that is not good for the environment.

What if we are not news conscience, and we take a trip abroad to a foreign country, and missed a US travel advisory saying that there is a high risk of being kidnapped in that country, or even a high risk of catching a disease that is really contagious and spreading fast in that country.
Then we are seriously putting ourselves, and maybe our family at a high risk of serious complications.
What would people do, because they were unaware of what was going on in the world around them.
I think that we are responsible for keeping up with the news, because it is our responsibility to be informed about what is going on iaround us, at least for most of the time.
As a matter of fact, I read a news article just the other day about some serious Joker virus that was infecting Android smartphone applications.
It drains people's bank accounts.
If I didn't read the news about, I would not have known that my wife had one of those apps on her phone, and we would have been clueless about where our money went.
Be responsible, be aware.
The year is 2087, and on December 15, all members of the world met together to put an end to World War III.
For the past 11 years, members of the world fought over limited resources, and conflicts of interests between the NATO and WARSAW, which had formed once again with new countries in the year 2060.
For many countries, the massive war was a costly endeavor, not only taking the lives of 15 million around the world, but devastating the lands of the countries where many battles took place.
For 50 years, countries complied to the agreement, going into isolation and focusing on recuperating its losses from the war.
Most of the countries of the world had deceived the US, fooling it into going into isolation while the other countries remained connected.
For many, it was the only way to truly recover from the war, as they lacked resources to repair and restore its many cities and infrastructure.
Many countries worldwide were deceived, not just the US.
Yes, many were deceived and found themselves struggling in the past 50 years to recuperate their losses.
The US, despite the isolation , had managed to recuperate its losses and had become a world power once again.
However, other countries had managed due to the same, with the help of other countries that assisted them by feinting isolation.
The US despite feeling deceived, decided against starting a new war, realizing the futility of engaging with other countries that could easily counter with its own military might.
However, the United States did not want to be left out and thus formed its own alliance with other nations who were similarly misled.
There was a numerable amount of countries that had gone into isolation, many of which were once enemies of the US in World War III.
Forming a new alliance, the US offered aid and military support to those countries, which in turned accepted such support by joining the alliance.
The other countries were not so quick to form such alliances, and found themselves forming smaller groups that were overshadowed by the new US alliance.
The US alliance, later known as the Allied Nations, grew into a dominant force and soon emerged as the strongest alliance globally.

Although they avoided further conflicts due to a mix of diplomacy and military force, it was unsure whether many believed that the Allied Nations would continue to avoid major conflicts, much less a war.
For many, the Allied Nations was a pivotal event in history that stemmed from the isolation that lasted for many for 50 years.
Whether the isolation would truly avoid conflict in the future, was unknown.
But for the past 50 years, the world saw a peace from the devastation that was World War III, a peace that many believe would not be ever seen in the future.

Of course schools should be providing free pads and tampons to students.
I should point out, right from the beginning, that I have never experienced period shaming or period poverty.
As you might have guessed, I am a member of the other half of the population, that will literally never have this experience.
However, as a member of the human race, I feel it is necessary to look out for the needs of those who do.
Currently, in the United States, although Title 10, Section 5131.6 of Law states that public schools should provide menstrual and breast-feeding supplies to students.
So it is already a matter of law.
Since laws can be changed, however, I hope to convince you that these programs should not be cut.
Before I move on, I want to briefly discuss toilet paper.
Imagine if you had to rush to the restrooms between classes, and once you were finished, you realized that there was no toilet paper in your stall.
You politely ask the person next to you to pass some under the walls, but he or she refuses.
This other person tells you that you should have planned ahead, and, besides, your bodily functions are disgusting and you should not be talking about them.
Does this sound far-fetched to you?
It should, because no one would behave like that other person.
And yet this is what women and girls are subjected to on a daily basis when it comes to their periods.
They are ridiculed and humiliated for simply performing a necessary, normal bodily process.
And if they can't afford the necessary sanitary supplies, or simply can't afford them, many people have no problem in blaming the victim.
We say that she should have planned ahead, or should have been more responsible.
This is simply unacceptable.
Schools should be prepared to help these students because it is the right thing to do, and also, because students will not be able to learn otherwise.
IBesides, i the schools already have free toilet paper, soap, Band-Aids, etc.
then they should also have free pads and tampons.
All of us are equal, and all lives matter (as some opponents of my viewpoint are eager to point out), so we all deserve some basic accommodations.
Toilet paper, soap, Band-Aids are all necessary to our health.
They are not free, yet we never think twice about providing them in public to those who are in need, because health and sanitation are important and necessary for everyone.
Reproductive health should be treated the same as any other public-health issue.
If toilet paper is essential for all students and a matter of public health, then pads and tampons are equally necessary.
If you have some objection to the cost of these supplies, just ask yourself if you would be willing to give up free toilet paper, soap, and Band-Aids in public.
If it's not acceptable when it happens to you, then it's not acceptable when it happens to anyone.
And that is, literally, all there is to say.

You feel instant panic sneaking up on you, because you know that if you move, you'll be stung.

You ask why he's asking for your orders and he says that he's your loyal servant.
Interesting, you think to yourself.
You have never met a servant bee before, and it's odd that at age 34 you are finally meeting one now.
You request his assistance in alleviating your allergies.
But all of a sudden, you feel a sharp pain in your shoulder.
You glance downwards and notice that you have been stung by the bee.
You begin to panic as you sense your throat constricting.
You attempt to call out for assistance, but you are unable to do so.
You sense your body relax completely and collapse onto the floor.
You are unable to relocate.
You are unable to inhale oxygen.
You are incapable of thinking.
You feel your life slipping away, and you curse the bee for being so conniving.
You berate yourself for being so easily fooled.
You express anger towards the world for its cruelty.
You blame the universe for its perceived injustice.
Suddenly, your mom is at your side.
Tears are falling from her eyes.
Although her face is not visible, you are able to hear her voice.
She apologizes, sweetheart.
You're going to be okay.
Stay with me, honey.'
You sense your body being raised from the earth.
You then hear your little brother rush over and you know he's angrily swatting away into the air, trying to kill the bee that did this to you.
You sense your mom placing your body in the backseat of the car.
You hear the sound of the door closing forcefully.
You can hear the sound of your mother's car engine starting and driving off.
You sense urgency as you are taken quickly to the hospital.
You can hear your brother sobbing in the back of the car.
You sense your mother's touch on your arm and you hear her reassuring words, "Just wait a moment, my dear."
Just hold tight.
Once you arrive at the hospital, you hear the doctor say 'We need to act fast.
He's going into anaphylactic shock.'
Your mom starts crying harder and you feel the doctor's hands on your body.
The doctor suggests administering an epi pen.
If we don't, he will die.
The nurses swarm around you and you feel the doctor stick something into your arm.
You experience a sense of relaxation in your body.
You sense your airway expanding.
You sense your body beginning to breathe once more.
It's a total miracle but you feel so much better now.
You hear your mom express gratitude.
The doctors ask for details and your mom says 'He was stung by a bee.'
The doctors nod and gravely tell your mom that she must protect you from bees at all costs moving forward, because if you are stung again, you will die.
Your mom tells the doctors that she will do everything in her power to protect you, and that she thought she had drilled it into your head not to go near bees.
But your mom feels guilty because she realizes she recently planted some flowers in the front yard that are full of bees.
She didn't really think anything of it since she knew that bees are good for pollination and good for the ecosystem.
But now, thinking back on the situation she realizes she should have been more careful.
She never should have planted those flowers.
It's really unfortunate that this happened to you and your mom realizes it could have been avoided.
She apologizes profusely to you but you tell her not to worry because you're fine now.
The doctors are confident that your prognosis is good and you really don't want to worry your mom.
Later that night, you're discharged to go home and your mom makes you promise that you will never go near a bee again.
The next day, she takes action to help you keep that promise by pulling out all the flowers that she had planted in the yard.

The task force is transported to a city named New Jerusalem, where they are brought to trial for the wrongdoings of their forebears.

Joshua states that Kincaid is not a true prophet and that the nuclear war was not a divine punishment.
Joshua takes the task force to the ruins of Washington D.C., where he shows them a computer that was created by the government before.

The computer contains a recording of the last president of the United States, who tells the task force that the nuclear war was not sent by God, but by a group of scientists who wanted to destroy the world.

School can't teach you everything that you need in the world.
However, it can teach you how to be disciplined in pursuing your goals.
Discipline is having the willpower to follow through with doing what you know is the correct course of action, even when it is difficult or undesirable.
I remember many times in school where I wanted to do something more entertaining instead of my schoolwork.
I wanted to read a book or play video games.
I had to learn to focus on my responsibilities instead of my desires.
Besides being disciplined, I believe creativity is an important skill that should be learned in school.
Creativity is the skill of thinking in innovative ways.
I do believe that this is a skill that can be trained.
In school, I took classes like art or even my speech classes that focused on creativity.
At first, I was afraid to be creative.
With time, I learned to start thinking outside of the box more.
Creativity allowed me to solve challenging problems inside school and outside of school.
When I face challenges today in my job, I think back about certain tasks in school that focused on creativity.
For example, in one of my classes we had to write a series of papers that were judged by the class.
At first, I was very afraid to write outside of the norm.
My classmates judged those papers very harshly.
I discovered that in order to achieve success, I needed to think creatively and outside the norm.
When I took more risks with my writing, my classmates responded much more favorably.
With discipline and creativity, I think you can accomplish many great things in your life.
I do believe that these valuable lessons helped me to achieve a lot in my life.
I also believe these two skills will continue to benefit me as I get older.
Life will always throw problems at you that you haven't experienced.
I wish for my children to acquire these important teachings in school.

We should be concerned about how screen time affects our children, our families, and our communities.
W should also be worried about the impact of screen time on our health care system, our economy and our society.
Screen time poses a significant public health concern.
We spend hours each day, hunched over a screen, squinting at a blue light.
We are lacking sufficient physical activity, sleep, and quality time with our families.
We are also lacking sufficient time to contemplate, introspect, and engage with ourselves and those around us.
As our excessive screen time affects our posture, it causes us to ache from bad positions, have headaches from the light.
We become irritable, as we don't feel well.
We don't talk with people any more, and suffer silently by ourselves.
Our unhealthiness and bad feelings spread to our family, our friends, our community.
From there, they spread to the world.
The coronavirus pandemic has ended, but a new pandemic has begun.
Record suicides and anxiety abound.
Depression and feelings of loneliness are commonplace.
We are all experiencing negative impacts from spending too much time in front of screens.
We need to make a change in our screen-time, in our health and in our society.
It is necessary for us to power down our devices and spend time outdoors.
We should go outside and get some fresh air, engage in physical activity, and spend time with our loved ones and neighbors.
We should focus on the fundamental aspects of life.
Our livelihood and health depends on us returning to a simpler time.
in general My experience with dating apps has been great.
Thanks to Tinder and OkCupid, I have been able to meet and date some really cool people.
In fact, I am currently dating someone I met on Tinder.
I met her at a bar, but we connected on Tinder first.
The first date went well and we have been seeing each other ever since.
I think that we would have never met if it weren't for Tinder.
I believe this relationship will last because we have a lot in common and we are both very similar.
When it comes to Netflix, I think the effect on dating and relationships is neutral, and trivial.
Before Netflix, people would go out to the movies on dates, or rent a movie, or watch TV.
Netflix is just another way to do that, the 21st century way.
Social Media has made it easier to stay in touch with friends and family, and has also made it easier to meet new people to date.
I think its effects have also been generally positive.
The only downsides are that it can be a distraction, and it can be used to spread negativity.
Checking up on a partner's social media accounts can be a good way to see if they are being honest, but it can also turn into a way to spy on them.
Again, though, before social media existed, paranoid people would still check up on their partners, and it caused the same problems in relationships then, that it does now.
Social media is just a new way to do it.
Texting is a great way to stay in touch with people, and it is also a great way to flirt.
Emojis are a great way to easily express flirtatious or emotional sentiments, and texting enables plenty of that.
Texting is also quick, and convenient, and not only does it enable new relationships to blossom, it helps to maintain existing relationships and keep them strong and healthy.
In short, technology has been a great boon to dating and relationships.
It has created many new ways to start new relationships, and it has also made it easier to maintain existing relationships.
It has some downsides, but those downsides are not new, and they are not unique to technology.
So, the new things it has introduced, have been more than worth it.

Those who participate in the sport purely for recreation or adrenaline may promote a rationale for doing dangerous activities like skydiving, rock climbing or ski jumping, But what is the goal of the sport?
What defines winning?
What determines a loss?
How do the rules determine what's fair and what's unfair?

It all seems a bit pretentious, even if it's a thrill -- not to mention expensive -- to hurtle oneself off a high cliff or summit if there is not a clearly-defined way of doing it well or poorly, or right or wrong.

But if the goal of the sport is to achieve a specific outcome that has not yet been achieved, as in trying to travel farther or higher, that increases the risk of someone getting hurt or damaging something.
Engaging in reckless and irresponsible actions is often accepted if it only affects those directly involved and does not have wider repercussions.
Is it considered selfish to continue participating in a sport that is clearly hazardous?
I think so.
Reckless behavior goes against the concept and principles in sport, which is honor, integrity, fairness and respect.
Acting responsibly is something that should be frowned up, especially in competition.
Athletics instill important values and principles that guide our decisions and choices in life.
That is why we should aim to label activities as sports only if they promote or sustain the value of sports.
Otherwise, it's just a dangerous game.
Dangerous games have consequences that must be faced, and I don't want those to taint the idea of what sports are.

Lei lines deep beneath the earths surface have been dormant for eons.
Now, as the world faces imminent destruction, these lines are beginning to throb with the energy of the ancient deities.
The mana is rising through the lei lines to the earths surface and the few humans who can tap into it are becoming the last hope for the survival of the human race.
A woman stands in a field, set to gather any edible plants that haven't been damaged during the fights between the human and aliens.
A warmth enters her core, filling her body with a heat that is both frightening and familiar.
Her toes and fingers tingle, he concentration becomes more focused.
She senses the energy of the earth coursing within her.
But what to do with it?
She thinks back to the books she's read, the games she's played and movies she's watched.
Is this magic that she's feeling?
Is the mana in the lei lines the same as the mana in the stories?
Straightening her arms, she points a finger and thinks'we need food'A blue glow appears from her finger and slowly glides across the ground.
10 feet in front of her is a small patch of ground with small fronds growing from it.
She bends down and touches one of the fronds.
She can sense the growth of the tiny plants, she can sense the transfer of nutrients from the soil to the plants.
Soon, a row of carrots appear in the ground.
She rushes home to tell her family of her discovery only to stop abruptly in the alley behind her house.
The alley is permeated by the scent of blood and echoes with cries of distress.
She sees lights flashing in the house, the lights of the aliens that have been neutralizing the human race.
She feels her core warm once again and realizes this could be the one thing that saves them all.
She rushes through the door and sees her father, mother and brother being held by the aliens.
She points her finger at the alien and thinks 'This is how I will end them'The mana shoots from her fingers up a wall and out a window where the ground begins to glow once again.
The intensity of the light increases steadily until it becomes overwhelmingly bright.
And then she sees it.
More carrots popping from the ground.
The extraterrestrials are feeling perplexed.
Her family is confused.
And then she realizes, the mana isn't a weapon.
It is only there to provide food.
The aliens cackle and turn back to the family, now standing by the woman.
With a sharp pain, she realizes she had no hope.
Despite having magic within her she will die.
A bright flash, a scream and then nothing.
At least the family was together until the end.

For many in the past, it was not expected that one could know anything that was going on beyond their country or community, given the lack of technology such as the internet, social media, or even television and other types of viewing devices.

Traditional media in those eras, such as newspapers were often locally controlled, and opinionated from a particular point of view that did not encompass all the perspectives and opinions prevalent in the world at the time.
While people could be argued to be better informed of the local events that would affect them, today I believe people are much more informed of what is occurring all around the world.
As a result of various factors, we might feel we have a greater responsibility to keep up all types of events, even ones that occur internationally alongside with local and national events.
However, such a feat is difficult if not impossible for many citizens of the world.
One possible reason for struggling to handle the vast amount of information available is a lack of time.
For most people have obligations to account for, in addition to taking the time to get informed and stay up to date with current news and events.
Some have less time to keep up with the news, spending a lot of their waking time at work and other obligations.
Others can have more free time to stay informed, which in too can lead to other actions such as political engagement and activism.
The citizens with less time on their hands to keep up with the news are not necessarily worse than those that do, nor would I consider them bad citizens.
In fact, I don't think it is possible for many to keep up with all current events, however I believe it is still their duty to at least stay informed regarding certain news and topics.
A person that has a basic awareness of events that occur in the world can accomplish a lot more than they might believe.
Just having a simple understanding can be useful in avoiding catastrophic events or harmful situations.
For this basic awareness people have coincides with the possibility they will spread what they know to others, and inform people of what events they are up to date with.
With the prevalence of technology, this means people will know about the news more readily, especially with the impact of social media in connecting people with relevant information.
This will lead to action, as there will be people who can do something about certain events, whether it is voting, protesting, and much more.
It is vital that people stay informed about the news, but due to time constraints for most, they might not keep up with all the news all the time.
Nevertheless, based on past experiences, even those with the most time constraints can have a positive impact on the world if they share take action themselves.
Today, you are mentally and physically healthy.
Although as you would find, it wasn't your original body that you woke up in.
You found yourself reincarnated, as a newborn to a new family.
You somehow were still aware of your past life.
You realized that you must have died in the hospital yesterday, lamenting that your old body was deceased.
You worried about your old friends and family, who were likely mourning your death.
Eventually you come to terms with your situation, realizing it would be pointless to fret over something you can't change.
You would have to grow up as a new person, and hopefully accomplish more than you had in your past life.
As you continued to mature, you began to notice that things were not quite right.
Although you were in a different body, you were surprised that many things that happened in your past life also happened in your new life.
Surely you thought, the concept of fate wouldn't apply to someone that was reincarnated?
But there was too many coincidences in your life that you felt were too eerie and strange for them to be just coincidences.
In your past life, at the age of 10, on your birthday you ended up breaking your right arm, after falling out of a jumper.
Sure enough, on your second 10th birthday, you ended up breaking your right arm as well, this time after falling out of a tree.
When you turned 18 and got your license, you ended up getting a speeding ticket on your first drive alone, just like in your past life.
You were convinced that your new life was following the path of your old one.
That idea worried you, as you wondered if your new life would end up in the same manner as your previous life.
You tried to push that thought away, trying different distractions to forget it and to enjoy your life.
However, it became harder and harder for you to ignore the possibility.
Especially as you are the same age when you first died, when at the age of 27 you got in a car accident after leaving work.
You realize that such a thing could happen as well, and feared that you would experience the same fate.
You try to remember the same date as the first accident, believing it was a wednesday in April, which was next month.
To try to change fate, en every wednesday in March you would call in sick or use a vacation day to stay out of work.
You even tried taking public transportation or walked to avoid driving on other days.
May came soon enough, and you realized you had potentially changed the fate of your life.
You feel asleep on the last day of April, content you were still alive unlike your past life.
On the first day of May, you woke up in a strange room surrounded by equipment.
You realized you were back in the hospital, having come out of a month long coma.
You realized your new life was but a dream, something your mind conjured during the coma.
You would soon be discharged the next day, and return to your original life.
Your family and friends were relieved to see you alive and well, and you too were glad to see them again.

You thought back to your own life and to the life you experienced in your coma, and you realized that despite all the hardships and struggles you experienced in both, you were quite grateful for the life you have had so far.
Although you would always wondered if reincarnation was something that would happen to you when you would die, you also accepted the possibility that it didn't exist.
You were motivated to live your current life to the fullest, feeling you had much more to experience and do in the remainder of your life.

I think that it is important to know what is going on in the world, but I do not think that it is necessary for everyone to watch the news because my kids do not watch the news, just like normal kids.
Does that make them bad citizens?
No, it does not.
It is also in my opinion that it is impossible for adults today to not watch the news at all anyways because the news is everywhere.
Even if it is not consumed by traditional TV methods, it is still all over social media, the internet, and even on the radio.
As well as that your friends, and co-workers are a source of some form of the news because they spread it via word of mouth, and you watch them when they are talking to you for the most part.
Even more so, since everyone consumes the news in one way or another, I do not think you can call anyone a bad citizen based on their consumption or lack there of, of current world events.
I do think that most people only keep up on the news that they themselves, or those around them, would be at all remotely interested in.
For instance, I believe that someone who is not interested in sports would not stay informed about sports news.
Someone who is not interested in what's going on in, let's say Italy, is going to watch the news about Italian affairs like someone from that area would.
Basically, no, I do not think that someone who does not watch the news is a bad citizen at all.
A student athlete getting paid would not the economy of universities.
The amount that these schools make off of the student athletes is incredible.
We're talking about millions and in some case billions of dollars and the student athletes don't see a cent of that.
I do understand the point that student athletes would become a bidding war for universities that have a lot of capital.
I don't see that as any difference than free agency in sports.
Typically the highest bidder will win but there are some cases where an athlete wants to be close to home or takes a hometown discount.
At the very least, the student athlete should have to weigh those options.
The easy way to solve that issue as well is simply to limit the amount that a student athlete can make.
$250,000 is a fantastic salary for a student athlete and is life changing money for any 18 to 22 year old.
You can put a specific criteria on the salary such as maintaining a 2.0 GPA each semester or their salary is forfeited or at the very least a portion is.
This allows there to be fair competition between the universities and a school like Alabama won't be able to simply outbid a school like Syracuse.
Student athletes are working as a full time athlete and a full time student.
Shouldn't they be paid for their efforts?
What happens if a student athlete gets both a academic and an athletic scholarship?
That student is punished if they get a full ride for both categories.
They are entitled to 2X the scholarship amount and instead just get one scholarship amount.
The business of college athletics has been a scam for way too long.
Student athletes have been exploited by universities for far too long.
You have coaches like Clemson's Dabo Swinney saying that student athletes shouldn't be paid and that he'd retire if they did.
Well, a bill was passed that allows student athletes to get paid for their imagine and likeness.
Did Swinney retire?
Of course not.
He makes upwards of 10 million dollars a year.
Imagine that.
A coach making 10 million dollars a year while his players make absolutely nothing.
Again, a scenario where most logical and reasonable people will look at and say 'that is unfair.'
The only people who will say that it's fair are the people that are making tons of money off of those student athletes.
Luckily, more and more people who have power have seen this issue and have acted in the student's favor.
I look forward to more laws and bills being passed that allows student athletes to get their fair share of money.

My dependence for screens is very much like a drug.
I do not know what do with myself one day when my computer broke and I needed to purchase a part and it has not arrived yet.
I was going crazy.
There was more to life than checking my e-mail every few minutes or browsing the Web for background information to support a presentation.
Sure, having access to phones and computers all the time has its benefits.

For one, there are plenty of ways this digital age allows us to communicate with people across the globe, and there are also lots of ways we are able to educate people without the need for one on one contact, specially during the time of the pandemic, when it is mandatory to keep distance from other people.
But it's definitely ruining my life.
The same way how drugs overused can ruin someone's life when they're addicted to it, overly involved in computer, video games or other applications is the same.
There was nothing interesting to do in my house, nor in my neighborhood, or anywhere in the town, and I became totally dependent for my entertainment.
I did not want to communicate with people, because there was nothing to talk about and I was tired of it.
My social intelligence and how I connect with people have become a bit damaged, only because I was left alone with this computer and now, I never know what to do with myself when I'm out in the open.
It's very scary.
So yeah, while I do not want humanity to go back to the Dark Ages, when there were no electrical devices invented, I do not think it will be a good idea for humanity to go through another Dark Age.
And there's no denying that having all the humanities' knowledge and information at your finger tips is not a bad thing.
But at the same time, aspects that you normally do not consider that's being damaged like social intelligence and the ability to remember things, are negatively impacted.
Our reliance to technology has to be limited at one point, not just because it is a good practice to do if you want to keep your life on track.
As for me, I will try my best to contact more people I know and if we can return to normal, possibly even go to the town once again.
Find more people to communicate with, and try to carefully pick and choose what technology, video games, programs or apps I decide to use.
Screen use will not go away any time soon, but we shouldn't be too dependent on them to the point it hurts our abilities to connect with other people.
Remember, technology was made to help us, and not to be addicted to.
All of human history has seen paradigm supplant paradigm: rock paintings, then oral histories, then the printing press, then radio, then TV, then the computer, then AR and AI and social media.
Are any of these 'better' than the others?
Or is each the product of a unique zeitgeist that will never come again?
Each one is a reflection of the time and location it was created in, and each possesses its own distinct worth.
Looking forward, I am sure than in 100 years, in 200 years, all manner of human interaction will take place of which we currently only dream.
Brains in vats (how's that for isolation)?
Personality uploads at the moment of death?
Brain transplants?
No doubt if any of these come to pass, they will be bemoaned as the end of 'true' humanity, of 'true' human interaction.
But they won't be, any more than pay TV was the end of the cinema!
But for now, I am happy to be on my screen., and my phone, and my computer.
I am happy to be in my time.
Because one thing is for sure: it will never come again.

It's okay if someone is indifferent or prefers not to be informed about what is happening.
I believe it is important for citizens to stay informed and make an effort to do so.
I don't know that any one person can actually do anything to change the larger social issues, but I think it's worthwhile as a way to participate.
I believe you should take advantage of any opportunity to voice your opinions on political issues, whether it be at work, school, or within your community.
If you choose not to, I don't believe you are committing any wrongdoing.
I believe that individuals should not feel guilty for not actively discussing or writing about political issues or communities that are happening far away and not directly affecting them.

If you have a choice, sure, the world could use another person with an opinion and a chance to write something for the internet, but it's not like you're doing anything wrong by caring more about the local community, or work, or family, or friends.
Do you believe that the events reported in the news are having a meaningful impact on your life or on society as a whole?
Do you believe that staying informed about current events and actively participating in political affairs can lead to significant change?
Does this level of awareness impact your life in any way, either positively or negatively?
The answers are different for each person.
The president's recent overtly racist statements about immigrants are affecting my life.
Someone threw rocks threw rocks at the car next to mine with political stickers telling immigrants to go back home.
I ended up paying $300 to fix the collateral damage.
The news spreading globally will have a significant impact on our society.
Can I make any real difference?
Probably not.
I can have my opinions and hopes and dreams, but I likely can't do anything that will effectively change policy in any substantial way.
I can engage in activities that make me feel like I am actively involved in the world.
I prefer engaging with strangers in public instead of keeping to myself at my own table as an introvert.
I make an effort to keep up to date with local and state political news.
I strive to create environments where individuals from diverse backgrounds feel protected, and I am not afraid to address instances of discrimination when I encounter them.

I understand that I may not be able to have a significant impact on the world that can be daunting and intimidating. However, I find comfort in knowing that my words and actions play a small role in the larger picture.
I feel that I can make a change at local level, and pay attention to the news I see involving my community.
But I don't judge those who feel differently.
They're not bad, just have a different perspective than I do.
He's tall, handsome and extremely muscular.
He is the type of man she has always fantasized about.
The guy that every girl dreams of marrying.
She is confident that he is the man she has been waiting for.
The issue is that she doesn't know that he's actually a shapeshifter.
The man asks her to go on a date to a fancy restaurant.
When they're on the date the woman realizes that this man is perfect for her.
Everything is going well, they are getting along and laughing and there is a charm in the air.
The woman is filled with joy and chooses to proceed with a second date.
The second date however doesn't go as well.
A drunk man comes up to their table and tries to hit on the woman.
The man ends up getting in a fight and knocks the man out.
This upsets the woman because there was no need for it.
She can stand up for herself.
The man apologizes to the woman but tells her he would do it again and that nobody hits on his woman.
The woman is appalled and breaks things off with the man.
The man ends up chasing her in different disguises as he is a shapeshifter and finally gets her when she is vulnerable again.
He shows up as a similarly handsome man but with blonde hair, facial hair and even more muscles this time.
They go on a date and everything is going well.
They go on a second date and everything is going well.
They go on a third date and the man gets on one knee and proposes to her.
The woman is shocked because they had only been dating a month.
She thinks back to her previous relationships and how they felt.
She knew this one was special but one month felt so short to make a life long commitment to someone.
However, the woman didn't care and took a risk.
She agreed to get married to the man.
They had a wedding date set and that day was fast approaching.
The wedding plans were going smoothly, the woman was excited as was the man.
On their wedding day however, something terrible would happen.
The man was getting ready to say his vows.
He was extremely nervous.
So nervous that on accident he revealed his true self instead of the faux muscular, handsome man that he was.
The man ended up being an obese man that was balding.
The woman was shocked.
She knew that she shouldn't commit so quickly but she felt something special.
The bride ran outside of the venue and all the way home.
She was crying when the man walked in and explained to her how sorry he was.
The bride didn't care and demanded that he leave.

The long-term issues were horrible as she had PTSD and trust issues.
A man had taken advantage of her mind when she was vulnerable.
He ruined her wedding day.
He ruined the most important day of her life in front of all of her friends and family.
It was a cruel stunt by the man.
Luckily, 10 years later the woman finally got back on the dating scene and found the man of her dreams.
She ended up marrying him and they had 3 kids, 1 of which ended up being a professional basketball player.
The woman was happy and was one of the best moms of all time.
Her struggle was real, but she was able to overcome it and see the other side.
She finally was at peace and was happy.
You have the world at your fingertips.
It is time to reclaim our power.
The setting of the game is a world where Mana is the origin of all power.
The objective is to win the game by adding the most Mana to the collective pot.
You can earn mana by participating in card games.
Each card is either worth Mana or holds the power to take Mana from another source.
Players take turns playing the game.
The turn consists of two parts: the first is the draw phase and the second is the action phase.
A card is drawn from the stack.
Then, the player must play a card and be left with 5 cards.
During the action phase, players have the opportunity to use their cards.
The player chooses the card to play.
Next, the card is placed in front of the player.
The amount of Mana on the card will match the amount of Mana on one of the source wells on the board.
The player must move to that location on the board.
The player can then take the Mana from that source well and wait there until their next turn.
There are also cards that allow the player to gain Mana from a source well without having to move their piece.
This gives players the advantage of collecting more neighboring bonuses and obtaining Mana.
The game concludes when the final card is taken from the pile.
The winner is the player who has the highest amount of Mana.
If the game is being played in tournament mode, then the winning mana goes into the collective pot, and is divided up between the players before the start of the next game.
James Ernest and Patrick Rothfuss collaborated on the creation of the game.
It is among the first games to be published by the newly formed Patrick Rothfuss Enterprises, a game publishing company owned by Patrick Rothfuss.
A new version of the game was released in 2017.
For more information, visit the official website.
It is sold by Amazon.com and other online retailers.
Social media accounts for the game include Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram.
I don't remember how I got here, in this dimly lit, heavenly cinema with all of these people.
I try hard to remember what happened previously by asking the people in the cinema where we are.
The person in front of me turns around and says 'be quiet, the show is about to start'.
To my surprise, the person in front of me looks similar to me, but with a subtle difference in facial structure.
When I face the people behind me, they appear to resemble my previous lives.
I soon realize and remember, that I died in a tragic car accident at the age of 36.
I was driving back from celebrating my birthday when a drunk driver collided with my vehicle.
Even though I was wearing my seatbelt, I did not survive such an impact.
All of a sudden, I find myself watching a movie on the large screen in front of me.
The man in the movie is a reincarnation of myself, but with subtle differences.
I quickly understand that this film is going to mark the beginning of a new chapter in my life.
It feels odd to watch yourself live a life from the outside.
The life portrayed on the large screen in front of me closely resembles my past experiences, with slight variations.
In this life, I work at a big hospital, as a well respected surgeon, quite the difference from being a lawyer previously.
This person is getting ready to perform a surgery on a small child.
I recall bringing my kids to a petting zoo when they were young.
I always enjoyed watching them try out new experiences.
It makes me wonder how my children and wife are doing, knowing that I have died.
I understand that it is no longer about my past life, but about my reincarnated self.
I am no longer concerned about my loved ones' well-being, as I am confident that they will be okay.
I am somewhat relieved knowing that they will be looked after.
I continue to watch the movie in front of me, hoping that my reincarnated self with have a great life.
While watching the movie, I observed that my next life appeared to be better than my previous one.
This self was more extroverted and daring, which was the complete opposite of myself.
This individual was leading a life that I admired and it appears that everything is going smoothly for them.
He seems to have a lot going for him, a great family, kids, the works.
I am no longer sad about my passing, as I believe that my reincarnated self is now living a much happier existence.
I decided to stand up from my seat and walk out of the cinema, to see what waited for me on the outside.
As I step outside, I am surprised to find that the movie theater I had just been in had disappeared.
In front of me was a beautiful city filled with skyscrapers and people going on with their daily routines.
The architecture was built out of beautiful, golden, steel, brick and marble.
The streets were neat and tidy, with friendly passersby greeting me with smiles and waves.
Soon after, a man approached me, who went by the name Peter.
I quickly understood that this man was Saint Peter, the gatekeeper.
He offered to take me on a tour and to meet the person in charge.
We strolled through the beautiful city for what felt like an hour.
Finally, we reached a set of giant, golden doors.
I immediately knew that this was where the creator of our world resided.
I was never much for the belief in an almighty being, but I guess I was wrong.
The doors open and Peter points me in the direction of the creator.
I approach the creator feeling a combination of admiration and astonishment.
The creator is a woman, not a man as we were taught on Earth.
She tells me that I lived a good life, with people who loved and respected me.
It made me feel better about the whole situation.
She tells me that I have the option to either continue with my current life or start over from the beginning.
It was a tempting offer, to go back to Earth and live with my loving family, but I know that it was the wrong decision.
I enjoyed my life for what it was and now it was someone else's turn to live their life in my body.
I express to the creator my desire to carry on with my life, believing that I have the potential to have a positive impact on the world.
She smiles and sends me on my way back to the city.
Peter then takes me to my residence and gives me a job.
I am confident that I have made the right decision in choosing this life, and I am looking forward to experiencing all the joy it will bring me.
I know that I can make a difference here and help people.
Instead of being a lawyer, I have been chosen to be a doctor, like my reincarnated self.
It is nerve wracking and exciting at the same time.
I have always been intrigued by medicine and blood has never been an issue for me.
Maybe it was why my reincarnated self became a doctor and not a boring lawyer.
I am happy that I get a second chance to do something exciting and more fulfilling in this new life.
I know that one day I will be with my family again, and we will be happy here.
My time on Earth came and went, and for that I will always be grateful to have had the opportunity to experience a mortal life.

; they do not have the ability to make choices, and they are not responsible for their actions.

So, an animal that is suffering cannot be responsible for its suffering, while a human who is suffering often is.
IThisibeing the case, t is tight thing tdo focus on animal welfare when humans are suffering because we have a moral obligation to help those who are innocent and cannot help themselves.

In fact, if we were to focus on the well-being of humans instead in this situation, we would be doing something wrong.

I'm also sure that the people who raise this issue, and insist that animals are less important that humans, are the same people who would not help humans in need.

Helping animals is important, and moral, and so is helping humans.

'Well, are you going to try to enter my house or not?
', replied the pig from the comfort of their home.
The wolf looked up and down the house, and paused before speaking, 'I don't know man, it's kind of weird.'
The wolf was usually accustomed to breaking in to typical houses, made up of wood, brick, or some other cheap material.
But depleted uranium was a whole other matter, it was certainly much more sturdier than the previous houses they had broken into.
'Well, I'm going to bed, you can try to break in if you want, but I'm not going to be up for any longer, spoke the 92nd little pig to the wolf'.
And sure enough, they went into the comfort of their bed, wondering a bit if the wolf would break into their house, while they slumbered.
The wolf still outside, looked up at the house, and thought about how to get in.
They blew on the doors, the outside walls, and even tried scratching the windows, all seemingly resistant to his claws and might.
He tried climbing up the house, but found himself loosing his grip and unable to reach the roof.
The wolf was getting frustrated, he had usually entered a past household by now.
The wolf opted to experiment with a new strategy.
He saw the ground, and dug deep into the dirt.
Surely he could tunnel into the house if he could not break down its doors, he thought.
But upon digging deep into the soil, he struck the house's foundation, and found that it too was made up of depleted uranium.
Drat, the wolf thought, he was not going to get into the house.
The wolf then decided to head elsewhere, hoping to find a home they could break into, one that was not made of depleted uranium.
Sure enough, the 92nd little pig woke up early next morning, feeling very refreshed.
They slept soundly, and noted that the wolf had failed on entering their home.
They went outside to check if the wolf was still present, only to discover that he was no longer there.
They were relieved, there home was safe from the wolf after all.
So they went back in and started breakfast.

While they had lived in fear in the past, scared of all threats and scares their mother would warn him and his siblings before they left the home to make their own, they were now confident that they could live in peace, without fear of the wolf or any other predator.
It was a new day, and a new life for the 92nd little pig, and no wolf or threat could ever take that away from them.

There is an entire generation of young people who are growing up without a clear understanding of who their true friends are or what it truly means to have a genuine friendship with someone.
It's so much easier to be mean to somebody on the other side of a screen, and then you can just 'unfriend' them.

Children are developing without the knowledge that they can openly express their emotions to others.
It's all about, 'I'll send you a message, and we'll use texting and chatrooms instead.'
People are being held away at a distance, instead of being able to sit in the same room and talk to somebody.
It's a completely different style of interacting with others.
We're all living in our own little bubbles, instead of being out in the real world--seeing who we're really friends with.
Social interaction is increasingly unbalanced, as technology has become people's primary and solitary companion.
We're all so busy trying to tweet the best hashtag, or say something that will get a 'Share' or a 'Like,' that we're not taking the time to acknowledge the human being right in front of us.
We're in the middle of what I worry is becoming a permanent societal isolation.
My mother had a meeting with a teacher at school who informed her that the children no longer use the playground for playing.
They possess iPads and are seated at a separate table all to themselves.
There's no crossing over and talking to each other, or hearing a different voice than their own.
They do not listen to narratives, or experience the sensory elements of the story.

I worry that the hearing and speech development of young children is being damaged, because they're not using their mouths or their ears to hear and understand the different sounds of real-life speech.
A lot of individuals struggle to stay seated quietly because they are constantly seeking mental stimulation.
Children are growing up at a faster pace than any generation before, and they're not learning how to deal with real humans.
I fear that we are becoming a generation devoid of human connection and face-to-face interactions.
We may not acquire the ability to understand and manage human emotions, including empathy.
The physical world is increasingly being replaced by the digital world.
I believe that we are at risk of losing our human nature.

Since the dawn of time, people have managed to establish intimate relationships by meeting each other in real life, gradually learning to trust one another, and eventually being at the point to where they really want to begin a relationship with each other.
21st century technological developments have only added a layer of bizarre complexity to this process, and have further isolated people to the point where this process fails before it can even begin.
Dating apps are the greatest example of this.
I've used them, and the experience is not unlike playing online poker, or playing video games -- the main point of it is to kill time in lieu of having better things to do.

The way the time killing process works with them, is that, you open up the app, conveniently right around the time you would otherwise go to bed, and start swiping through dozens of unappealing or phony users until you find one or two that you like, and begin exchanging messages with them, which might then end in a flaky or disconnected face-to-face interaction, which might then end in a crappy date that doesn't lead to anything further, which then leads you back to the beginning with yet more profiles of people you don't have anything in common with, and who you don't really want to meet.
This does nothing to build a foundation of trust and rapport, and it does nothing to help people connect with each other.

Netflix is a mere time waster, it's much like going to a video store, only with thousands of titles rather than hundreds, few of which either you or a prospective partner will have any interest in watching, and the whole process is more likely to result in awkward silence and resentment over poor viewing choices, than a romantic connection.

Texting is very much the same way -- the only difference is that it sucks even more time out of your day, and takes more from your life, as you fail over and over to communicate with someone like a real human being, and wind up resorting to emoticons.

What all of these things have in common, beyond being ineffectual for dating or relationships, is that they are all means for some greedy corporate entity to make money, and ultimately if you build a real relationship, the money making will stop, so they have interest in facilitating relationships.
The best response is to ignore them all, and meet someone in the gym, library, a book store, coffee shop, or on a hiking trail somewhere.

Then, once you're in a relationship, you can rest satisfied, knowing that not only have you met someone you might spend the rest of your life with, you've also saved a ton of money in the process and helped to put Netflix out of business.
