Growing up, my mother always told me that I was allergic to bees.
She would tell me that I should stay away from them at all costs because it would hurt a lot.
She did not want to scare me as a child, so she never told me that my allergy could be fatal, but as I got older I learned otherwise.
I always avoided spending too much time outdoors, fearing that a bee would get close to me and sting me.
I kept my fear of bees to myself and never displayed it to others.
Outdoors, my mother always protected me from bees, but when I left for college, she could no longer protect me.
She warned me many times to be careful on my own.
I consistently assured her that I would be okay, but internally, I was filled with fear.
I stayed in doors as much as I could in my first two years of college, quickly running from building to building in order to avoid any bees.
I made sure to cover up with long sleeves and pants at all times, even during hot weather, so as to prevent getting stung.
My friends never questioned my actions and accepted me for who I was.
During my third year of college, I made the decision to work a summer job in the city.
My summer job was being a waitress at a hotel spa/pool.
I had to serve customers inside of the hotel, but on occasion, I would need to go outside by the pool.
One day, I met a nice boy out by the pool and we got to talking about school.
I was so engrossed by our talk, that I forgot I was spending too much time outdoors.
I was relaxing in a lounge chair next to the pool when I sensed a bee alight on my shoulder.
The boy I had met told me I had a bee on my shoulder and I was paralyzed with fear, running back inside, hoping the bee would fly away.
I got back inside the hotel and discovered that the bee had remained on my shoulder.
I was about to swat the bee off my shoulder, when suddenly, I hear the bee say, 'Your Majesty, what are your orders?
I could not believe my ears, I thought I might be hallucinating from a bee sting.
After observing that the room was empty, I chose to pose a question to the bee.
'Did you call me Majesty?
', I said to the bee.
'Yes, I am your Majesty's personal bee.'
I told the bee that my mother had always told me that I had a deadly allergy to bees, so I lived in fear of bees.
The bee reassured me that I did not have a severe allergic reaction and that my mom had deceived me.
I wondered why my mother would lie to me about something so strange.
The bee informed me that my mother had not been completely truthful with me because she was the queen bee and was trying to shield me from potential threats.
I asked the bee who my enemies were and the bee said that my enemies were the wasps.
Since I was unfamiliar with wasps, I decided to inquire with the bee about their identity.
The bee said that wasps were the ancient enemies of bees, caught in a long war throughout the centuries.
The bee told me that I was the princess bee, and that I was the only one who could end the war between bees and wasps.
I asked the bee what the first order of business was in the war against the wasps.
The bee informed me that our first task was to locate the queen of the wasps.
The wasp queen had been living in Europe, all the way across the world from my home.
I informed the bee that I planned to travel to Europe in search of the queen wasp.
I boarded a flight with my personal bee in tow, and flew to Europe.
I discovered the nest of the queen wasp in a German village.
I was about to walk in to her home , when suddenly, my mother arrived before me.
She informed me that she was aware of my intention to travel to Europe in search of the wasp queen and had arrived to prevent me from doing so.
I told my mother I had to do my job as the princess bee and stop the longstanding war.
My mother said the war had been ongoing for such a long time that trying to end it would be futile.
Nevertheless, I pushed my mother aside and knocked on the door.
An old woman opened the door and I asked if the wasp queen lived here.
The elderly woman claimed to be the leader of the wasps, while I declared myself as the royal bee.
She had been expecting me for many years and invited my mother and I in.
We were seated at her table when she mentioned that she had been patiently anticipating my arrival to bring an end to the war.
She had been the leader of the wasps for far too long and had seen many casualties.
The war between bees and wasps was pointless in her opinion and she wanted to make things right.
I informed her that I was in agreement with her and expressed my desire to rectify the situation.
My mother, the wasp queen and myself agreed to end the war and we signed a peace treaty.
The treaty also established a partnership between bees and wasps, so that we could work together and build a better world.
I was filled with joy to have brought an end to the war, so I embraced both my mother and the queen of the wasps.
My mother and I left Germany and flew back home, knowing that our future looked bright.
I no longer needed to fear the outside world.

Let's start with dating apps.
Before the advent of stuff like Tinder and Grindr, you had to go out to bars and clubs or to parties if you wanted to find someone with whom you were interested in dating.
The odds that you would meet someone you really liked were pretty slim, but still, you had to do it if you didn't want to be alone.
It also took a lot of time and effort, and frequently that time and effort was wasted.
Since the advent of apps, this is no longer the case.
You can do the same thing, with the added advantage that you can do it from the comfort of your own home, and you can do it whenever and wherever you want to.

I'm not sure that the odds of success are greater, but since it takes less effort, and since the result is substantially the same, you can find someone you like a lot more easily... and then talk to him or her without wasting energy and cutting into your schedule in the same way.
I could say similar things about Netflix.
Before Netflix and the like existed, you and your partner had to rent movies from the video store or go to the theater.
The selection was limited and it was often difficult to find something that both of you would enjoy.

It became a repetitive, frustrating ritual, going to the video store, looking at the shelves, putting stuff on hold, waiting for it to come in, then watching the movie and often feeling unsatisfied afterward.

Renting a bummer of a movie often led to arguments about whose fault it was for renting that title, and not finding stuff you both wanted led to arguing about how you should have gone to the theater instead.
With Netflix, you can still end up with bad movies, but the consequence is less severe, and most of the time, you can find something you both want... even if it's different stuff.
Texting, compared to prior methods of communicating, is superior in its speed and lack of pronouns.
It's quicker than a call, and it avoids the problem of people being on different schedules and talking at different times.
It is somewhat limited in what it can communicate, but in many cases, that's a plus, because it reduces arguments about what's being said and read into.
On the whole, it's made staying in touch with partners much easier and more enjoyable.
And that's kind of my take on all the 21st century innovations in dating.
They haven't fundamentally changed the things that you need to do to establish and maintain a relationship, but they have made doing all of those things easier and more convenient.
What could be wrong with that?
I think that it is a good idea for schools to have free pads and tampons on hand, but I don't think that they should be required to provide them to every student.
Schools are ultimately a place of learning.
They don't have the responsibility to feed or clothe children-this is the parents' duty.
Schools could provide period products as a last resort, similar to school lunches for impoverished students.
Parents are responsible for providing their kid with number 3 pencils,  school clothes, and lunch.
They are also in charge of supplying their child with pads and tampons.
If parents are unable to provide these items, then the child should be able to go to the school nurse and ask for them, but only if their parents have forgotten them.
Period products are cheap- a 100 pack from Walmart costs less than an hour of minimum wage work.
Parents are the providers, schools are the educators.
A clean separation of these makes it easier for the student and parents to understand personal responsibilities.
Each child is unique, and parents will know their kids best.
They provide personalized attire, learning tools, and food, and should teach reproductive responsibility as well.
Period products should be like spare pencils-available at the school, but only as a last resort.

The initial book in the Mana series, titled The Last Mage, can be purchased at this time.
It is a book that takes place in the 1800s.
The protagonist is a youthful boy named Will who possesses magical abilities.
It is his responsibility to fight off the witches that are trying to poison the Earth and all it's inhabitants.
The witches fly on brooms and have the ability to cast spells onto any human they come into contact with.
The main objective of the witches is to eliminate all humans and gain control of the world.
However, Will is a boy that has superpowers.
He possesses the power to manipulate the wind and control the rain.
He also possesses the capability to soar through the air.
He can make the conditions impossible for the witches to fly in.
He can make it so windy that their brooms won't be able to be steered.
Will decides to challenge the witches.
He sees them flying out and about one day and gets into a battle with them.
The witches fire spells at him and he used his ability to control the wind to dodge them.
He utilizes his power over rain to extinguish the fire the witches are using to harm him.
Will and the witches go their separate ways and prepare for a final battle.
Will figures out a way that he can defeat the witches.
The next time that they try to burn him with fire he will control the rain so that it won't hit the ground.
The rain will just stop at the witches brooms height.
The broom will get so wet that the witches will fall off and fall into the fire and perish.
The final battle has finally arrived and Will is fighting the witches.
It is a stalemate to start but Will knows he has an ace up his sleeve.
The witches play right into his plan and place a pit of fire underneath where he is flying.
The fire begins to spread and covers the entire ground.
Will recognizes this and instantly makes it rain.
However the rain stops right at broom level.
The rain is coming down like a downpour.
The witches try their hardest to hold onto their broom but they slip and fall into the fire pit and are never heard from again.
Will help saved his community and all the members within it.
He was seen as a hero.
He saved humanity.

'Another little pig who I can try to eat!'
The wolf didn't know that the house was made of depleted uranium.
This was because the little pig had a rare mutation that allowed her to live there without a hazmat suit.
The wolf approached the house and tapped on the door.
The little pig knew it was the wolf, and called out, 'Please wait there, right beside the house.
I am busy.'
So the wolf sat on a bench made from the wall of the house and relaxed.
The small pig went into the kitchen and prepared a sandwich.
Then she sat down and ate the sandwich while watching television.
The wolf fell asleep on the bench made of depleted uranium.
Hours later, he woke up and yelled through the window, 'Hey there, little pig, are you still busy?'
The little pig said, 'Come on in, you can wait inside.'
She unlocked the door and ran to an inner room and bolted and locked the door and went to sleep.
The wolf entered the house after opening the door.
He looked around, but the little pig wasn't anywhere he could see.
So he went to the kitchen and made himself a sandwich with the supplies the little pig had used earlier.
Then he sat on the couch and read a newspaper.
The wolf fell asleep on the couch.
When he woke up, he felt a little sick.
So he went back to sleep.
When he woke up again, he felt very sick.
He went to the bathroom and looked in the mirror.
He was turning green.
He was also much smaller.
He was transforming into a frog.
He said, 'Ribbit.'
When the little pig heard this, she knew it was safe.
She greeted him by saying, "Oh, so you've transformed into a frog."
Let me get the door for you so you can go to the water.'
She pulled the door open and the frog leaped away.
And this was how the 92nd little pig made sure she would be safe from the wolf.
Taken aback you shake your head only to hear the same tiny voice say 'Your Majesty?

your voice rises as you grow confused and upset.

'But, but, but...' you stutter 'I must be going crazy, how can a bee talk to me?

There is no one around you other than a bee.

you shout to the bee'Your guards!?

you reply'Your mother!?
YOUR MOTHER!'

'We are your people, your Majesty.
The bees, the butterflies, the winged ones, the pollinators.
We are all under your command' the bee says in a respectful tone.

you ask'ABSOLUTELY NOT, dirty creatures spiders!

The bee says in disgust.

you ask'We want you to come with me, to the hive, to meet the queen.

Things are changing perspective and growing larger.
No.

I cringe from these types of characters because I not only find them lazily written and one-dimensional, but that they are a negative addition to any show, book, or movie, that has consequences to its viewers.
Not only do such characters illicit negative responses from other people who find them offensive, but they also perpetuate negative ideas and responses about these character groups in the real world.
Many people hold stereotypes towards racial groups, as well as other types of minorities.
Stereotypical characters reinforce those stereotypes and thus become a way to perpetuate and even justify negative and stigmatized attitudes towards those character groups.
This can lead to said groups being viewed as lesser, even potentially dehumanized.

I cannot say that I am willing to accept those characters in any media or content that I consume, given that their presence or implementation are not necessary, or a meaningful addition by the writers or creators of said content.
For some pieces of media, if the portrayal of a stereotypical character is too offensive or disingenuous and a critically seen part of the content, then I will either avoid that show, book or movie.
Seeing such characters are not pleasant for me personally, which is also true of other people, and I don't enjoy engaging with shows that overall make me feel uncomfortable or negative in some way.
While there are shows that can make me feel sad or even uncomfortable with what it depicts, in those instances those are intended in either a more thought-provoking way, or respectful manner.
I am not referring to those types of cases, and instead refer to how stereotypical characters can feel insulting and unrealistic in the context of a show, movie, and book.
They are rarely thought-provoking or meaningful in the context of such media, and could be rewritten to be much more respectful, or even more relevant to struggles of the group.

Often times, it feels as if creators don't take the time to script stories relatively authentic script about characters or groups, but instead prefer to rely on stereotypes which are easier to implement, and take significantly less time.
If I feel that I am not being valued or respected as a viewer watching the show or reading a book, I would prefer to read or view something else.
I am aware that creators have many more dignified methods to depict characters in their shows, movies, books, etc.
than the ones that portray them as no more than stereotypes, and those are a better use of my time.

As viewers, writers, consumers, and individuals with other identities who are not well seen in media, we have an obligation to demand better representation, and for others to create as such to reduce stereotypes in society, not reinforce and perpetuate them.
I disagree with the statement made by Cody J. McDavis.
McDavis admits these student-athletes generates a lot of money for their schools.
If you are generating large amounts of money for your school, you should certainly get a piece of that income.
If you look at events like the NCAA Basketball tournament,  you will see that these events generate millions of dollars for those involved.
The NCAA Basketball Tournament brings in a value of $8 billion for CBS and Time Warner, just as an illustration.
The reason why this tournament is so valuable are only due to the players.
It is not fair that we have corporations and schools that are making billions of dollars off of the work of student athletes.
Don't you think these student athletes deserve a share of the funds?
In any business, the workers who are helping to sell the products of the business gets a wage.
These student athletes are selling and producing the product--sports.
How about compensating students for their participation in activities?
Ultimately, I believe there are many organizations who do not wish to share the profit with these athletes.
They understand that their share of the financial pie goes down when the athletes are allowed to sit at the table.
McDavis mentions that paying athletes would create an unfair advantage for big sports programs.
However, that is already occurring.
Big sports programs already have many ways to attract top talent.
Student athletes are producing a very valuable product.
They deserve to get a cut of the profits that their schools and other corporations are getting.
They deserve to receive a fair piece of the pie.
I primarily dated potential romantic interests through in person connections and interactions, from my time in school.
I also did not use dating apps, given that they weren't as prevalent as they are now, nor would I say they were as effective or helpful as they would be now.
Thus, I preferred to avoid using dating apps, and instead chose to date people without finding first on a dating app.
Nevertheless, dating apps, I believe, can give people otherwise more romantic opportunities than they would have otherwise through more traditional means.
Dating apps are quite useful and beneficial for many to try out, especially if they struggle to discover and find people to date.
Additionally, I do think that dating apps allow for people to more easily meet potential romantic interests for long-term relationships, allowing them to date with less complexity than otherwise.
For that reason, I believe dating apps will persist long into the future, being well implemented in how others date as well as other technology that is being refined and improved upon as well.

Like dating apps, technology like Netflix, social media and texting also enables people to connect with each other regarding romantic encounters, especially in the instances where that may be difficult.

For dating and romantic relationships, being able to communicate and talk your partner is critical in maintaining trust and a romantic connection, which leads way for a solid relationship or a long-term partnership.
Even for short-term relationships, communication via text and social media can improve how positive you view the interactions you have with others.

The technology available today has many good benefits to it, in the sense that it allows for us to make connections with others easier and faster, something that can be seen how ubitquitous it is in romantic and non-romantic relationships.

Although there are some negatives associated with technology use, specifically when people fail to moderate and balance it well with other aspects of their lives, I believe many would be able to learn and implement how to best use technology in their life.

If anything, as time goes on, the technology people use for romantic interactions and dating will get more and more refined, ensuring more positive and favorable outcomes for the user, and potentially ensuring more relationships are made and sustained.
Animals are not really capable of fending for themselves or living on their own the majority of the time.
So when an animal is suffering or beaten, it sort of is similar to a little baby being beaten.
As far as people being more upset than they are to people, i think we are just desensitized when it comes to human suffering.
We see it so often in the news, media, movies, etc.
We kind of just feel it is normal, and we know that people are going to do mean things sometimes.
I think in a way, if were to be so upset about it each and every time we would drive ourselves crazy mentally.
Needless to say, people still do get upset at humans suffering as well, i think the actual news of it though is just a little densensitized.
You dont hear about dogs suffering in the newspaper or on the news, but you do with people.
I think we as people realize that animals are left out of media sometimes, so when we do hear about their suffering it is almost like it is in a spotlight.
Also, people find animals to be much more innocent and adorable in comparison to humans.
When you see a cute dog all you want to do is love it and protect it.
I think part of this instinct comes from the fact that they cannot really fend for themselves often times, and need someone to help them.
Its the same feeling you would get if you saw a infant that was left outside by itself, or if you saw someone harming a little baby.
The baby can not protect itself, so your instinct is to go and help it.
I personally dont feel it is wrong to focus on animal suffering, as i feel that if you are focused on helping anyone that is suffering it is a good deed.
As far as where to dictate our funds as a country, i think it would be smarter to help people out.
Helping people out would be an investment anyway, and this would allow those people who were helped to help out the animals.
The more healthy people we have, the more homes we have for these animals.
As far as testing products out on animals and what not, i think this is going to happen regardless.
Unless we allow experiments on people, animals are simply going to have to take the burden here.
The meat industry will probably never go away either.
Humans were brought up eating meat, and there would be many deficiencies if we just stopped eating meat all together in my personal opinion.
I get some people may be different, however i think that for the large majority of people meat consumption is important.
The best thing we can do i would say would be to treat these animals right and give them great lives while they are here.
So in conclusion, i dont think it is WRONG to focus on animal welfare, however i feel that human suffering is a larger problem.
This is the tale of how you and the rest of the Lost Generations manage to endure.
in a world where everyone younger than you never ages, but everyone older than you avoided the side effects.

You, personally, were lauded throughout your life for discovering the drug that stopped the effects of aging in a younger population, but the government decided, in principle, to deny you the chance to benefit from it.
You were offered the drug,bfrom the black market ut you refused.
You, and many others like you, were outraged at the government's decision, but some of the others took the drug anyway.
For the most part, you just live your life as normal in this new, boring world where young celebrities never age, and never get replaced by younger counterparts.
Eventually, the outrage about the unfair distribution of the drug dies down as well, and the older generations accept their fate.
If anything, the economy thrives, because people no longer lose their vitality as they get older, and they have decades of wisdom and experience to apply to new projects.
You and some of your generation are still nostalgic for the past, but you accept that a world without aging, even if just for a few, is better than the world that we had before.
Even though you won't be around to enjoy it forever, you are glad that many others will be.
When you are halfway into your happy retirement, however, the side effects become clear.
This whole time you thought that everyone had stopped aging, but it turns out that they spent the decades aging very slowly.
The rate at which they aged was itself slowing down, and only recently had they reached the point where they truly did stop aging.
You and the rest of the Lost Generations are now the only ones who are aging normally., and the younger people who took the drug still appear to be young and healthy.
However, in recent years, it has become clear that they are actually now aging in reverse.
They are moving backwards through their growth cycles very slowly, but the age at which they are going back is increasing steadily over time.
If this trend continues the same way as it did when the drug was preventing aging, then eventually, they will all become babies again!
The only hope for humanity is that these 'young' people start to quickly have as many children as they can.
They all just have to hope that their children will age normally, just like the unlucky lost generation who never got to take the drug.
The only source of comfort that you have in your old age is that you won't be around long enough to see the terrible impact that this side effect has on the world as a whole.
You are also glad that enough time has passed that people don't remember who you are.
If you thought they were mad when they couldn't get the drug, you can't imagine how mad the people will be when they learn what your miracle drug really accomplished.
'Thank god for our short lifetimes', you think to yourself.
You turn off the news, and decide to take a long nap.
THE END

Goodwill towards living creatures can't be segmented neatly nor should it be stifled in any case.
Isn't the premium we place on human life over animal life a clearly biased stance?
I think we should show empathy towards every living being.
Care of one type of lifeform will only increase the value that we put on all life in general.
This is not a case of a well with limited water but of a capacity for love that can only be strengthened through use.
Therefore, we should commend people for caring for animals.
It's important to remember that many animals that now exist were basically created, in their current form, by humans.
Thus we have a responsibility for their wellbeing.
Further it shouldn't surprise us that humans care for animals so readily.
We are also creatures of the animal kingdom.
And in some ways animals embody the most innocent aspects of our own nature.
If humans stopped caring for animals we would not compensate by caring more for other people.
On the contrary, our overall empathy would decline dangerously.

hhe many cities and it citizens of the world depended on Mana, to power their homes and electronics, as all of human technology at that time used it as an energy source.

As chaos and panic rang all over the world, they looked into ways to replenish Mana and have it flowing all over the world to power the technology critical for modern civilization survival.

You drive to a quiet beach on the Outer Banks of North Carolina and head towards a cozy bungalow.

He offers you a beer from a cooler by his feet and you sit next to him.
'So Barack, you ever get tired of retirement?'
'It has its upsides, but after running the most important country in the free world, I have to admit it's boring sometimes.

JFK smiled and grabbed a beer for himself out of the cooler.
He explained that he thought he was dead, too, but about 20 years ago, he woke up in a lab.

What do you want me to participate in?
Restore America's greatness.
Obama raised an eyebrow at that response.
'America is great already, and will be better once Trump is out of office.'
JFK told Obama that Trump and his allies were trying to rig the upcoming election in Trump's favor.

creen time also helped us tstayconnect edwith friends and family.

The wolf wasn't too happy to learn that the little pig's house was built out of depleted uranium.
After all, what good was such a house to him?
He knew he would never be able to blow a house like this down and thus it would make it very difficult to make a snack out of the little pig.
Of course, the little pig was a smart little creature and understood that was the whole point of building his house out of depleted uranium.
The wolf was a bit frustrated when he realized that he'd need to find another way to make a snack out of the little pig.
He determined to deceive the small pig in order to get it to come outside.
He decided to figure out what the little pig's favorite foods were.
He discovered that the young pig enjoyed eating pizza, drinking beer, and indulging in ice cream.
One day, the wolf came by the little pig's house with some ingredients to make homemade pizza.
The wolf said to the little pig, "Hey, I have the ingredients to make pizza at home."
Do you want to step outside and assist me?
The little pig laughed.
Why would he come outside his house to make pizza?
It wasn't as though there was an oven built into his backyard.
But the wolf gestured at the pig through the little pig's window and showed the pig that he had brought an outdoor grill with him.
'I was thinking we could grill the pizzas together,' he said.
The small pig was curious.
Grilled pizza was delicious!
To seal the deal, the wolf said, 'I also have an ice chest full of cold beers and pints of Ben and Jerry's.'
The small pig was bought by someone.
The little pig opened up his door and approached the wolf.
The wolf expressed happiness that you chose to step outdoors.
I was worried that you would be very inflexible about this.
The piglet chuckled and replied, "I'm not boring or unadventurous."
I am clever enough to realize that if I were to step outside, you would devour me.
The wolf smiled at the little pig.
'So then what made you change your mind about coming outside?'
he asked.
The small pig returned the smile.
'Once I saw how much food you brought over, I figured that you'd just get full eating pizza and drinking beer and eating ice cream.
I figured you couldn't eat all that and eat me too.
And besides, I love all these foods!'
The wolf smiled at how gullible and ignorant the little pig was.
The little pig's greed for the food had tricked the little pig into thinking that the wolf had a much smaller appetite than he actually had.
In truth, the wolf had plenty of room in his stomach to eat lots of pizza in addition to the little pig.
The wolf exclaimed, "that's fantastic, little pig."
Let's begin making the pizzas.
While the wolf rolled out dough, the little pig spread sauce and cheese.
But suddenly, the wolf turned to the little pig.
"Hello small pig, I just remembered that I forgot to bring the pepperoni."
Do you have any suggestions?'
The small pig shrugged its shoulders.
He wasn't a huge fan of pepperoni.
But then the wolf said, 'I have an idea!
I know exactly where I can get pepperoni.'
The little pig was confused.
'In what location?'
he asked.
The store was closed that day so there was nowhere close to get pepperoni.
The wolf laughed.
'I can get it right from you.'
And he licked his lips and ate the little pig in a flash, teaching the little pig a lesson about greed.
The lesson of the story is that small pigs should never place their trust in wolves.

The only time a sport becomes hazardous is when it is done carelessly.
One cannot label a sport, such as mountain climbing, as excessively risky without first specifying the reasons for why it may be considered reckless.
If someone deems mountain climbing as excessively risky, they are essentially stating that it is imprudent to attempt climbing a mountain.
One cannot simply use the term reckless and make everyone agree on the same thing.
We all have different standards.
To assume that we all think the same is not only arrogant, but is also an injustice against us as a free country with the freedom to be different.
Calling a sport too dangerous to be considered a sport is asinine because the definition of sport has changed over the years.
People in the past considered sports to be things like bullfighting and gladiator fighting; things that many would consider reckless by today's standards.
Hunting, fishing, javelin-throwing and archery all involved substantial risk.
If you were to inquire someone from the early 1900s about sports, they would likely mention boxing, horseback riding, or activities such as hiking and skiing.
Teddy Roosevelt engaged in the 'sport' of big game hunting and one of his companions was killed by wildlife during one of his hunting 'safaris.'
By labeling a sport as too risky to be classified as a sport, one is essentially eliminating a variety of popular activities enjoyed by mankind throughout history.
Each person has their own definition of risk.
Everyone has their own preferences.
Just because one person views high-risk activities as reckless, it doesn't mean that everyone shares the same perspective.
The value of a sport is primarily determined by how its participants personally assess it.
People evaluate something based on what they want out of life.
And we all have different values.

Having a smartphone has allowed us to substitute meaningful face-to-face interactions with impersonal ones, which can negatively impact our relationships.
Nonetheless, it enables us to establish connections with individuals with whom we wouldn't typically interact.
It is important to cultivate a variety of relationships and interactions in order to properly take care of oneself.
It is crucial to maintain relationships outside of the digital world.
I believe that technology is a valuable tool that goes beyond just being a distraction from our relationships with others, but I also think it should be used in moderation to ensure healthy balance.
Technology has greatly facilitated communication.
Prior to the prevalence of smartphones and texting, I would only communicate with my partner during in-person meetings.
Nowadays, I can stay in touch with him through texting and snap chat even when we're not together.
Technology can also serve as a means of sidestepping problems or difficulties in a relationship.
If we have a disagreement while we are with each other we can text or email instead of arguing in person.
It gives us time to cool off, and re-read what we want to say.
This way we can have a much less intense argument and deal with the issue in a civil manner.
Technology is a wonderful thing but can also be used dnegatively  I think there are also many negatives with the communication aspects of social media.
It has the potential to create shallow relationships.
I don't feel 'face to face' conversation is as important to people as it used to be.
We often end up communicating in these short texts that doesn't require as much effort and thought.
Posts can also be misinterpreted.
Dating apps frequently portray dating as a one-way, effortless experience.
It becomes more convenient to see dating as a form of entertainment or competition.
If an individual does not reply within a day or two, it is best to continue searching for another person.
You don't have the opportunity to fully understand the person as you would in a typical circumstance.
Today, the amount of technology being utilized is impeding the traditional dating process.
In dating apps, the key action is simply swiping left or right to move on to the next potential match.
There are pros and cons of technology.
We should carefully weigh the benefits to make sure they outweigh the negatives.
Technology provides social advantages for individuals who do not have friends or family.
But it can also hinder the organic and natural development of our lives.
All of this should be kept in mind as we use it!
The man pulls Rachel into a dark alley, away from the bustling city street.
Another man, John, happens to see Rachel getting attacked by the stranger, and decides to help.
He grabs the man from behind and shoves him away from Rachel into a pile of garbage bags.
After turning to face John, the man quickly flees.
Rachel is relieved that the man has left her alone, thanks in part to John, who helped her.
John and Rachel begin conversing and discover that they share many similarities.
Rachel decides to thank John by going on a date with him to a small, coffee shop the following day.
Rachel meets John at the coffee shop and they get to know each other better over cappuccinos.
Rachel gets a strange feeling that she knows John very well, but she can't put her finger on it.
She dismisses the feeling and they go on a few more dates, and they fall in love.
As time goes on, Rachel and John fall deeper in love with each other.
They choose to live together and eventually tie the knot.
Over the years, Rachel realizes that John has a habit of disappearing for a couple of days.
He consistently returns and consistently provides a justification.
John tells Rachel that he travels for business at work a lot and he has no choice.
Rachel agrees to it, but she still senses that something is amiss.
One day, Rachel goes to the store alone and tells John that she will be back shortly.
John stays at home and says he has work to do and catch up on.
One hour later, Rachel returns from the store and sees John in the backyard acting strange.
Rachel goes to the backyard to check on John and finds him digging a hole in the ground.
John is burying some shredded clothes, so Rachel asks what he is doing.
John informs Rachel that he is getting rid of some old clothes by burying them.
Rachel does not buy John's excuse this time and asks him what is really going on.
John confesses to Rachel that he is a shapeshifter and explains that he has been repeatedly dating her in different forms.
He tells her that he is madly in love with her and has been trying to get it right, so that he could be with her forever.
John reassures Rachel that she is the only woman he has truly cared for, promising never to cause her any pain in the future.
Rachel is shocked and surprised that John has been doing this for so long.
She does not know if she wants to stay with John or leave him.
She goes home with her parents and thinks about what John has told her.
She realizes that anyone who would go through that much trouble for her is someone worth keeping.
Rachel returns to John and professes her love for him, expressing her desire to remain by his side.
John tells Rachel that he will be more honest about his shapeshifting.
He informs her that he will give her advance notice before he undergoes a transformation so she can be ready.
Rachel and John go back in the house and spend the rest of their lives together, happily.
The Dads are taken aback to learn that they are now considered the least important or successful.
They decide to start a support group to cope with it.
It's a pitiful affair as they each week go to the meetings, feeling sorry for themselves.
One father is committed to improving the situation for all fathers.
He says that they can just go and change the number on their mugs.
Then their families and friends will think they aren't the worst dads anymore.
The rest of the fathers clap, stand up, and start to exit the meeting.
They go home and use pens to change the number on their mugs.
The following week, they attend the support group together.
They share their experiences of what has happened since.
The initial father stated that he went back to his house and altered the number on the mug.
He says that it resulted in his wife being impressed.
She thought he must have been trying harder so he was thrilled.
He got recognition without changing anything.
One dad suggested that they just try and be better fathers and they wouldn't have to lie like this.
All of the dads laughed and said that was a good joke.
They then went back to stories of how changing the numbers had been such a success.
They then started to get greedy.
They began changing the numbers over and over, giving themselves a higher ranking.
They discussed the increased recognition and approval they had received from their families.
It was becoming an addiction.
Finally, one week they realize they had all now ranked themselves as the #1 dad.
They couldn't let their families see another dad's mug.
Then the praise they've been getting would stop.
They decide the only option is for each of them to all go live in the woods with their families, isolated from everyone.
They disband as a group and all go live as hermits with their families.
The families are miserable and the praise is gone, but they are happy at least keeping the #1 rating.
No one can take that away.
Dan woke up early that morning, as usual, had his cup of coffee, like usual, and sat down to watch the morning news, as usual.
Everything was as it always was.
To be honest, he was beginning to be okay with the fact that he would die someday - it wasn't the bitter disappointment is was almost 60 years ago.
But then the morning was 'as usual' anymore.
Dan was watching the news and witnessed the anchorwoman, a relatively new addition to the station, unexpectedly become paralyzed.
She looked about 22, the age most people got the drug, though some got it as early as 16.
She stood completely still, with wide eyes and a slightly agape mouth.
Staring at the paper and then the teleprompter in front of her.
She finally spoke, voice shaky, 'I'm sorry, we have breaking news.'
Last month the earliest recipients of the drug 4EvR all reported to medical centers complaining of headaches.
Within 6 hours they had lost their vision and hearing.
Within 24 hours they seemed to be comatose, though brain scans showed the same activity levels as a normal, conscious person.
They remain in that state.'
Dan stared at the screen in shock.
The newscaster continued.
'Scientists have been studying their condition and have come to the conclusion that it is due to the drug 4EvR.'
She began to cry, 'And according to their findings it is not only an inevitable side effect, but also one that is triggered or transmitted to users.

To summarize, all people who have ever taken 4EvR will almost certainly have been exposed to others who have been exposed to the original group and we should all expect to experience the same side effects within 2 weeks at the most.'
Dan switched the TV off.
He was in shock.
He had never taken the drug missing the age cut off by a mere two years, but all of his younger relatives had.
His children, his grandchildren, so many others.
Ans soon they would essentially be helpless with only a few aged people like himself to take care of them.
Dan was overwhelmed with anger out of nowhere.
It wasn't fair.
He had had expectations, and now everything was upside down.
This was not his problem to deal with.
He sat at his desk, and shaking, wrote notes to all his loved ones.
He wrote a note to his children, telling them how much he loved them, and how he was sorry that he couldn't be there to help them.
And then he went upstairs, and found the bottle of pills, the same ones his wife had used a few years ago when she just got tired of being old in a young world.
And he took many more than needed.
And left the world before everyone, just like he always thought he would.

Listening to a book does not provide the complete experience that reading it does.

There are some positives to listening to a book, such as being able to listen to a book while doing other things, being able to listen in places where you could not read, such as being in the car, or being able to listen to a book when you are too tired to read.
However, all of these things point to the reason it is better to read a book.

To get the most from a book, it needs your fully attention, the things that make listening to it attractive also mean you are not fully engaged, you are doing other things that need some of your attention.
I believe if you listen to it, some of the content passes you by, you miss out on some of the finer details and you miss the nuances that make a book great.
Listening is useful, and a pleasant past time, but it is not the same as reading.
So while you can enjoy an audio book, you will not get the same experience as you would from reading the book.
That experience allows you to gain more from the written text and understand what the author is conveying.
So, in conclusion, I believe it is better to read a book than listen to it.
The wolf paused, winced, and caught his breath.
'Isn't that overkill?'
The 92nd small pig replied, 'I disagree.'
'You've been through brick, stone, duralloy, and the 85th little pig's steel reinforced concrete house, but you're still coming.'
'I'm not coming for you.'
said the wolf.
'I've got to go to the bathroom.
Could you maybe help a poor wolf out?'
The pig smirked from the safety of his shell (and breath) proof housing.
'I'm not going to help you.
Just go in the bushes like the rest of your kind do.'
The wolf sighed.
'Fine.'
Then he skulked off to the forest.
That settled, the pig sat down to enjoy his new home.
He was on the verge of switching on the television when he heard a knock on the door.
It was, of course, the wolf again.
'What do you want?'
snapped the pig.
I am only here to express my gratitude.
said the wolf.
'Thanks for what?'
scoffed the pig.
I appreciate that you didn't assist me.
said the wolf.
'Why would you thank me for NOT helping you?'
asked the pig,  with more than a trace of skepticism.
I was able to use the bushes for the bathroom instead of having to go inside your house.
I also wanted to thank you for something else.'
'What is it now?'
asked the pig, his beady little eyes rolling.
'I wanted to thank you for encouraging me to think outside the box.
You see, I was so busy trying to get into your house that I didn't see the forest.'
The wolf continued.
'Plenty of stuff to eat out there, as it turns out, and it's not walled up behind depleted uranium.'
The wolf continued speaking as the pig considered this.
'As it turns out, me and my family have been wasting our lives, chasing after you for generations, when we could have been perfectly happy eating defenseless creatures out there.'
'That's great.'
said the pig.
'Anything else I can do for you?'
The wolf thought for a moment.
Sure.
Could I possibly forward my mail to your address?
I've moved out of my depleted titanium house next door, and I won't have a mailbox any more.'
And with that, the wolf and pig feud was ended, other than an occasional squabble over a lost package.
The news can be very depressing to watch.
Certain people may not be able to handle the mental stress that comes from constantly watching the news.
The news rarely covers good or uplifting stories.
Most of the stories are focused on crime, disasters, and negative situations.
Some individuals may be misled by the news into thinking that society as a whole is negative and unpleasant.
It can present a sensationalize view of the world.
For example, if a plane crashes, then there will be constant news coverage of the plane crash.
We have 24-hour news channels that will constantly cover the plane crash.
People who are highly influenced by the news may then think that airplanes are not safe to be on.
This is despite that the fact airplane crashes are generally very rare.
I think there are certain types of people that just don't react well to the news.
They are best focusing on the issues directly affecting them in their lives.
Ultimately, our number one responsibility in life is to take care of ourselves.
Anything else is good, but not a necessity.
You aren't a bad person if you don't keep up with the news.
In fact, you can still keep up with current events by talking with people.
Engaging with people who have actually experienced the current events may help certain people grasp them better.
We live during a time where the distrust of news seems to be at a high.
Are there moral implications intertwined with keeping up with the news?
No.
Whether you are good or bad citizen should not be based on whether you watch the news.

Paying athletes in the NCAA would compromise the integrity of the sport.
After college, the players have the opportunity to sell their skills in professional sports.
The time for the athlete to capitalize on their sports skills should not be in college.
If college athletes are being paid, I think that puts the student in a very powerful position versus the school.
The student could ask for a higher salary, or even bring up the possibility of leaving the team if their demands are not met.
The contract disputes that we see today in professional sports would occur in college.
I think this would be detrimental for the colleges that are involved in situations like this.
Overall, I do find Cody McDavis' argument to be persuasive.
I do think that larger schools would have a huge advantage when attracting players.
If a school has access to large monetary resources, I think that increases the chances of the best athletes going to that school.
I think the smaller schools would be at a very large disadvantage.
Once the best athletes come to the bigger schools, there is a greater chance that school will be successful in athletic competitions.
This further increases the chance that the best athletes in the future will come to that school.
I think it would be very difficult to quantify how much to pay the students.
If you are not a well-known athlete, should you be paid the same as a more well-known athlete?
How do we quantify this?
I think it creates a lot of unnecessary headaches for the school.
Overall, I think it would be better to just give the athletes a scholarship.
There are far too many drawbacks and not enough positives to students being paid.
I think that colleges need to really think hard about this issue before moving forward.

They are all personal hygiene items that should be provided for students.

Hence why before I said the schools should provide these items discreetly so no female student has to feel embarrassed.
I think ultimately schools need to step up.
School is supposed to be a safe space for children.
Maybe their can be meetings about this topic where only females are allowed to attend.
I can totally understand why females talking to males about this subject would be embarrassing nor would males really understand.

You realize your name is nowhere to be found on this list of dads.
You stare back at your mug, still unable to believe what you see.
You double check your eyes to make sure this isn't a hallucination.
You triple check.
Then your mind starts racing back to your wife Soeurette's pregnancy with Harper.
When Soeurette had shared the news with you that she was pregnant, she was already about 5 months along.
But thinking back on the situation, Soeurette had been with her brother, your best friend, Kaitlyn's husband, that one weekend that you were both out of town at a beer fest.
You had ended up getting called onto an emergency work trip that weekend and you had left the beer fest early.
You recall that Soeurette requested you to photograph her brother wearing the beer bikini that she created for him.
She had seemed overly flirtatious with him.
You recall the affectionate bond and intimacy between them as they engaged with each other.
You realize with great discomfort that the beer fest occurred five months prior to her pregnancy announcement.
You start to experience intense jealousy and anger surging through your body.
You begin to feel mortified at the realization that Soeurette had cheated on you with Kaitlyn's husband, your best friend.
You start to investigate the mug again.
You see that your best friend is listed as the 30th best dad in the world.
You experience a sinking feeling in your chest.
Your best friend doesn't have any kids with Kaitlyn, but now you are certain that he is Harper's father.
You come to the realization that you have been completely taken advantage of and deceived.
You are disgusted with Soeurette.
You hurl the mug at the wall and it breaks into pieces.
Soeurette comes to ask you what's wrong and you tell her you know that she cheated on you and that Harper is not your child.
Initially, she refuses to admit it, but you eventually demonstrate to her that you have uncovered all the details.
She becomes overwhelmed and admits to her wrongdoings.
She pleads with you to attempt to forgive her.
She expresses her love for you and states that she still desires to continue the relationship.
You ponder how you can remain in a relationship with a woman who has been unfaithful and taken advantage of you.
You kick Soeurette out of your life and let her fend for herself as a single mom to Harper.
She lives a very miserable and unhappy life after that and is never able to find another man willing to trust her.
She passes away alone, detached, and without any money.
Doing this would lead to the commercialization of college athletics and undermine the importance of a college degree.
Players on scholarship are offered free room and board, so a scholarship is essentially payment for their physical and mental commitment to the team and school.
If individuals desire to further their education, they choose to enroll in college.
If they want to focus on sports full time, they can go pro.
If they want both, they can find the suitable balance.
I think the main idea is that college is not the same as a job.
The aim of education is to create an atmosphere where students are exposed to and motivated to explore interests and perspectives that may not directly benefit them personally.
College is the fine-tuning of your skills, the exposure to new ideas, before you begin the commitments and worrying of life as a complete adult.
Compensating athletes would diminish the value of the college experience.
The value of a degree would drop, as graduates would essentially be viewed as professionals fulfilling their contractual obligation to the university (paying tuition and sitting through lectures).
The rest of the student body, the non-athletes, while still receiving scholarship money, would be expected to earn an actual living in the 'real world'.
This could pose problems from various angles.
Those who are not able to play professionally are deprived of the chance to do so.
to both 'earn and learn' simultaneously.
No other career path pays for attending college, so why should we single out athletes?
Those students who lack the physical abilities to participate in college sports are penalized for their limitations.
We should leave colleges as a sacred institution of learning...and let the unequal bartering of capitalistic professional teams begin once the students leave the door.
She feels drawn to him, but she is unsure about placing her trust in him.
She has had relationships in the past where trust issues have come into play.
They go on their first date and things aren't perfect but the woman sees enough in the man to go onto another date.
The following day, while the woman is working, she receives a call from the man.
He explains to her that he got two tickets to a broadway play and was hoping she'd agree to go with him.
The woman thinks it over and decides to go with the man.
The play that they are seeing is Wicked.
It is a play that the woman actually saw with her family as a child.
It brought back childhood memories for her.
She enjoyed the play and the man actually told her it was his first ever musical.
He somehow had intuition and knew what she liked.
She found that interesting as she never mentioned musicals or theatre on their previous date.
The woman remains uncertain about whether she can trust the man.
She has her guard up still and that wall is difficult to break.
She ends up telling the man that she doesn't want to see him anymore and that she's not ready for a relationship yet.
The man accepts her wishes.
Three weeks later the woman is thinking to herself and believes she had made a mistake.
She makes a phone call to the man and expresses regret for her actions.
She explains to him that she has been hurt in the past by other men and is just afraid to take a risk.
The man takes a deep breath and ends up admitting to her that he has the ability to shape-shift.
The woman doesn't understand what that means.
She asks him what shapeshifting is and he explains that he can change forms.
He can turn into other people, animals, inanimate objects, etc.
The woman is shocked and asks the man what he really looks like.
The man says that she has seen him in his original form the entire time.
He explains that he doesn't like to abuse that ability and prefers to show his real self for better or worse.
The woman begins to soften up to the man as he was honest with her.
She asks him how she's supposed to trust that what she sees really is his original form.
He tells her that he will show her that he can only turn into things that are within a 50 foot area.
He invites her to his home and she goes and sees that he's actually telling the truth.
The woman is emotional and tells the man that she appreciated how honest he was.
She agrees to go on another date with the man.
He tells her that he understands she has trust issues and will never break her trust.
His number one priority is to be loyal and honest.
The woman ends up dating the man for years and they finally agree to get married.
The woman is shocked that she was able to get over her past issues but she knows this man is the one.
He has always been honest with her, he has always been loyal to her.
She really believes that he will never do anything to ever hurt her.
And she ended up being correct.
The two ended up getting married and had 4 children.
They are currently living together and are in their 60s.
They rarely ever have any fights and have a love that is still as strong as the day they met.
Although it was an interesting and unique relationship, it is one that many people would die to have.
Two people with genuine long lasting love for one another.

I would not want to watch or read about all older people being fools, lacking technical skills and being a drain on public funds.
I suppose this is because I am one of those older people and none of that is true of me and pretty much every older person I know.
Ageism is a bad thing.
All stereotypes encourage discrimination that people justify on the the basis of the stereotype.
It can actually encourage violence and persecution of groups of people.
Look at what happened all over Europe under Hitler and his like-minded allies.
I believe that the best way to combat stereotypes is by demonstrating that they are unfounded.
The best way to do that is figure out what stereotype fits the profile of the person spouting off and turn it against him and use it against him.
I guarantee it will fire him up and he'll be denying most if not all about what you are pronouncing as the truth about him.

It can be based on gender, age, looks, skin color, religion, political stance, size of his feet, hands, nose, head, his height, or lack thereof, educational level, income level, clubs, favorite food and drink, anything at all.
It's not hard to figure out one that will fit or even a combination that will.
Hopefully, after that exercise the perpetrator will come to his senses and engage in some reflection that will will improve him as a human being.
No guarantee, but I'd say there is at least an even chance that it will.
Is it possible for this newfound power to prevent complete annihilation of the human race?
Nobody knows.
What they know for sure is that for the humans to have any chance to survive, they are going to have to be creative.
And that is a frightening proposition indeed given the circumstances.
In this case, the strong have been the ones that have survived, so the survivors are without a doubt up to the test.
Extensive training and effort are necessary for them to effectively control this new ability, but once they achieve mastery, the consequences will be severe.
The power itself goes by the name of short interval time travel.
It involves being able to send physical objects back in time, a method that isn't as risky as sending people.
This is simply a way to alter the future without going about it in too dangerous a way.
The survivors studied this skill for as long as they could and used it in order to survive the attack from the aliens.
Although the skill has yet to be perfected, those who are best at it ultimately have the best chance of survival.
Therefore, every survivor is advised to become proficient in this skill to increase their chances of staying alive.
The aliens are not a violent species to begin with but were forced into fighting when the humans became frightened and starting shooting and sending off explosions.
The aliens from their point of view came from peace, and only wanted peace from the interaction.
When provoked however, the aliens knew they had to fight, but still are not interested in war even after wiping out much of the human species.
Is it still a war of both sides are not fighting for something?
The aliens have decided not to look for any more humans, letting them die out on their own.
'Was it all some sort of joke?!'
asked the Vice President.
THe President shook his head sadly.
'No, it was no joke.'
He had just gotten off of the phone with the leader of the United Earth - it seemed that most of the nations of the world had joined the group - and learned the whole story.
'It was a desperate defense strategy.'
What is the plan for defense?
asked the Vice President.
What are you opposing?
'Us.
Or rather the US as it was back then.
You're only 45 right?
So you've only learned the cleaned up version  of our history and that war.'
Yes, but how is that relevant to the situation?
'Everything.
The President back then was ruthless, self absorbed, and determined to put the US in control of the whole world.
And our military was strong enough to do it.
If it hadn't been for the other nations of the world uniting against us, we would have won.
And even then, they were afraid of us recovering faster and trying again.
So they came up with a plan to trick us into voluntarily isolating.
There is a lot more, but that is the short version.'
'So what do we do now?'
The Vice President inquired.
'I don't know.,' said the President.
'I just don't know.'
Fortunately the population of the US did know.
They were not happy about being tricked into isolation, and they were not happy about the fact that the rest of the world had been working together for 50.
But they had become very practical over the period of self isolation and they weren't going to give up, or do anything rash now.
They planned to collaborate in restoring their country's stability and then shift their focus to addressing global issues.
And so they did.
With an emigration from the US to rival the immigration to the US of the old days.
US citizens moved to every country that would have them.
They brought their work ethic, their culture, and their determination.
And slowly the regained the trust of the world.
And eventually the US was invited to join the United Earth.
The US agreed to join and officially became a member of the United Earth.
And less than 50 years later, the first US territory citizen was elected President of the Earth.
And as people commonly say, the rest is now a part of the past.

Kids nowadays know how to TikTok and know every detail on their favourite movie (for example people such as Miranda Sings) but they have no idea what mistakes to avoid or how to handle different situations such as filing their taxes, registering to vote, or making sure who they vote for actually represents their opinions, or how to succeed in their job.

It's absolutely critical to have our usual subjects such as science and math, which are worth everything in today's world, but kids should also learn other subjects that I think are just as important, even though they get pretty much no attention anywhere, such as civics or politics, or how to achieve things rather than narcissistic topics.
There should be a restructuring in how students get admitted to college.

Instead of relying on the one board exam they do, which often tests knowledge in irrelevant areas, kids should be evaluated on how they handle themselves in their high school and how they interact in a team environment.
Because in reality, the student's lifetime careers involve them working in more group projects than they will ever deal with on an exam.

Let's also not forget that other life-saving lessons such as how to last in relationships, knowing how to deal with authority, and how to handle losing should be taught in schools for students' benefit.
There are too many examples that I am sure you know about news of kids that are getting pregnant or struggling through relationships striking over social media.

There are also a stark anger towards the police and how others see them, which I think stems from a lack of knowledge that authorities have rights to stop people just as much as you do, and that people are being falsely arrested because of this.
And lastly, let's not forget all about how there are too many school shootings that are happening in our country.

It's a very sad reality and I wish that at a very young age, our students get taught how to be aware of things that are happening around them, and that there are actual serious consequences to taking lives.
It's too easy to be angry and to be in the wrong mindset, when instead they could have an open mind to hear both sides of a story, even if they are different from the ones they are brought up with.

We should teach kids how to be tolerant to ideas that are different than theirs, because it's not often that they will be convinced to change, but they most certainly need to know how to live with people with vastly different mindset.

So there you have it, I think those three ideas that I have are the ones that should be taught more regularly in our schools today so that we could welcome more successful and more prepared bunch of our youth today to further tackle different issues in the future.

The world is changing, and they need all the help they could get so that they could be equipped with the necessary knowledge to tackle the different obstacles that come their way, and could potentially make it actually past their teenage phase.
I just hope we're not too late and there's enough hope left for humanity to survive and make it to the great future we were promised.

I enjoy reading, but I often find it difficult to find the time to sit down with a book.
But, with an audiobook, I can listen to the latest novel while I do mundane tasks that I have to do, such as laundry or dishes.
I almost look forward to doing tasks that would otherwise be lame without an audiobook.
Another reason I prefer audiobooks is that I don't have to tire out my eyes to experience them.
At the end of a hard day of thinking and staring at screens, the last thing I want to do to my eyes is stare at little letters on a page.
For this alone,  think audiobooks are just as good as reading.
Another advantage of audiobooks is one I don't experience personally but you have to admit it's fantastic that the vision impaired can experience books through audiobooks.
I understand braille books aren't cheap and it just seems like it would be more relaxing and enjoyable for anyone to listen to a book.
Another reason audiobooks are really great is that you can take it with you, unlike a shelf full of books.
You can carry a small device to a mountaintop and listen to 10 different books if you want.
I am unable to do that with books.
It would be silly to carry a shelf of books.
It may be silly to read for a week on a mountain too, but hey, the option is there, thanks to audiobooks!
All in all, there are far more advantages than disadvantages to audiobooks over traditional books and that is why I prefer them.
She starts seeing him romantically, and things are going smoothly.
Just as she was about to confess her feelings to him, a dreadful thought crosses her mind and she abruptly pushes him away.
The man gives her space but about two weeks later runs into her at a coffee shop.
They make small talk and the woman starts to realize she made a mistake.
Luckily for her, she receives a text on her phone from the man telling her how much he misses her and how he'd like to give it a go again.
She expresses to him that she would also like to try again.
The two have a date at a carnival.
The two of them are having a great time eating fried oreos and playing games.
The man even won her a giant oversized stuffed teddy bear by playing darts.
The woman is both shocked and comforted to see that the man has remained the same person even after their relationship ended.
She thought she had ruined everything but was beginning to think he was the one.
Months go by and the couple are getting closer and closer when the man finally admits to her that he is a shapeshifter.
She has actually been dating him over and over for months.
He had so much interest in her he couldn't let her go and had to find out what type of man she was interested in.
The woman is surprised by the news and tells him she's going to stay with her grandmother for some time to mull things over.
She speaks to her grandmother and tells her she can't trust the man because he tricked her.
The grandmother explains that while that may be true, she should really think about how much effort he put in to please her.
A few more weeks go by and the woman makes up her mind.
She is willing to give the pair another chance, but she is wary of being lied to once more.
She tells the man that he is to come of his normal form and they will go on a date.
The man agrees, respects her wishes and transforms into himself right in front of her.
The two go on another date and find they have a lot more in common than they previously had thought.
The woman asks the man why he tricked her and he explained that he had confidence issues and didn't think she'd give him the time of day.
He explained to her that he was attempting to determine the qualities of the man she was seeking, and discovered that he did not possess those traits.
However, the woman agreed to go on a second date with the real man.
And a third.
And a fourth.
They got so close that in the end they got married and had two children.
It was a fairytale of sorts with a beautiful ending and one that nobody expected.
Not the shapeshifter, nor the woman.
Fate is funny sometimes.
I think that schools should provide pads and tampons to students because it is a necessity just like toilet paper, soap, Band-Aids and other toiletries of the like.
As I am a guy, I have not ever experienced period shaming or period poverty, nor have I ever done those kinds of things to a person ever.
Schools should somewhat step in there because it mostly happens on their grounds, kind of making their responsibility to address such issues.
I think that pads and tampons are similar to toilet paper, soap, Band-Aids and other products that are already provided in schools anyways, because all are necessary when needed.
If you get a nasty cut on your arm at school, they send you to the nurses office to help you cover the wound so you are not getting blood everywhere.
Toilet paper,  well obviously they must provide that.
Just like soap, and the others, pads and tampons are needed sometimes for all students, not just the poor ones.
As far as period shaming, yes the school should step in the best it could and try to help those students that are being bullied.
Try to make everyone understand that a period is something that every single girl in the world has to deal with, and that it is just part of evolution and growing up.
That there is nothing that can be done to stop it, no matter how hard anyone tries.
Explain that no one wants to be bullied over natural, and perfectly normal body functions.
